{"title_page": "Orangi Town", "text_new": "\u201e\u201d{{Use Pakistani English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                     = Orangi|native_name=<br>{{nq|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u06cc}}\n|settlement_type          =  [[Municipality]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline            = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = OrangiTown Karachi.PNG\n|map_caption              = Union councils of Orangi Town\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = [[Pakistan]]\n|subdivision_type1        = Province\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Sindh]]\n|subdivision_type2        = City District\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Karachi]]\n|parts_type               = Union Councils\n|parts_style              = coll,para\n|parts                    = 13\n|p1                       = [[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />\n[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          = Town Council\n|leader_title             = Former Town Nazim\n|leader_name              = Abdul Haq\n|leader_title1            = Former Naib Nazim\n|leader_name1             = Shahid Bashir\n|leader_title2            = Municipal Officer\n|leader_name2             = Qamaruddin Shaikh\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 14 August 2001\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude           = 1 E+6\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 22\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_note          =\n|population_total         =1540420\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone                 = \n|utc_offset               = \n|timezone_DST             = \n|utc_offset_DST           = \n|latd= |latm= |lats= |latNS=\n|longd= |longm= |longs= |longEW=\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type         =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code              =\n|area_code                =\n|website                  = [http://125.209.91.254/CDGK/LinkClick.aspx?link=217&tabid=72 Orangi Town Page]\n| blank_name             = Office Location\n| blank_info             = Municipal Head Office Orangi Town No. 12, Karachi.\n| blank1_name             = E-mail\n| blank1_info             = orangi@karachicity.gov.pk\n| blank2_name             = Contact\n| blank2_info             = (021)36697869-36650833\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Orangi Town''' ({{lang-sd|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u064a \u067d\u0627\u0624\u0646}}, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646}}}}), often referred to simply as '''Orangi''', is a borough approximately 22 square miles in area that forms much of the northwestern part of [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]. When grouped with the neighboring municipality of [[Baldia Town]], the Orangi-Baldia population is estimated to be over two million.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasan|first=Arif|date=|title=The Case of Karachi, Pakistan|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Karachi.pdf|journal=|publisher=University College London|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The municipality was described in a 1999 [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] article on [[Mumbai]]'s [[Dharavi]] slum as the \"largest shanty town in Asia.\"<ref name=\"nationalgeographic\">{{cite web|url=http://seabed.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/index.html|title=National Geographic: Dharavi, Mumbai's Shadow City|publisher=}}</ref> Orangi is in fact largely a lower to lower middle class settlement, and only some parts of Orangi Town can be characterized as a slum.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jacobson-text?fs=seabed.nationalgeographic.com|title=National Geographic Magazine|date=|publisher=Ngm.nationalgeographic.com|accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[[:File:Principaux Bidonvilles.png#Raw data]]</ref> While Orangi is Karachi's largest largely unplanned settlement,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Satterthwaite|first=David|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hwWjv1vmED8C&pg=PA37&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwCXoECAgQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Water and Sanitation|date=2003|publisher=IIED|isbn=978-1-84369-479-3|language=en}}</ref> much of Orangi does receive municipal services. 90% of its streets are connected to sewage lines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1245044/karachis-orangi-town-named-largest-slum-world/|title=Karachi's Orangi Town named largest slum in the world|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2016-11-26|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/10/these-are-the-worlds-five-biggest-slums/|title=These are the world's five biggest slums|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> for example, mostly through the community-installed [[Orangi Pilot Project]], while 96% of homes have their own private latrine or toilet.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slums-pakistan-sewage-idUSKCN12D1PK|title=Fed up with no sewers, Pakistan's slum residents go DIY|date=2016-10-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> Over 90% of households in Orangi are connected to Karachi's electric grid.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Wignaraja|first=Ponna|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tg_5PJYFuW8C&pg=RA9-PA5&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwixqtrAocjoAhUEt54KHYa4DDw4ChDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Pro-Poor Growth and Governance in South Asia: Decentralization and Participatory Development|last2=Sirivardana|first2=Susil|date=2004-08-19|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0-7619-9798-6|language=en}}</ref> \n\nOrangi is bordered by [[New Karachi Town]] to the north across the Shahrah-e-Zahid Hussain, [[Gulberg Town, Karachi|Gulberg Town]] to the east across the [[Gujjar Nala]] stream, [[Liaquatabad Town]] to the south, and [[SITE Town]] to the west. There are 13 official neighborhoods, each with its own council, which has allowed the township to build its own sewer system.  \n\n== History ==\nFollowing Pakistan's independence, with a large influx of refugees from India moving into Karachi. The Pakistani government by 1950 began granting permission for refugees to settle on vacant land.<ref name=\":2\" /> Orangi was established as a townshp in this context by 1965.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Inam|first=Aseem|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ru4AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA238&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwBHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Designing Urban Transformation|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-135-00639-6|location=|pages=194|language=en}}</ref> Orangi Township was originally planned over 1,300 acres by the [[Karachi Development Authority]], and many of Karachi's squatter settlements were subsequently relocated here.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Wignaraja|first=Ponna|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tg_5PJYFuW8C&pg=RA9-PA5&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwixqtrAocjoAhUEt54KHYa4DDw4ChDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Pro-Poor Growth and Governance in South Asia: Decentralization and Participatory Development|last2=Sirivardana|first2=Susil|date=2004-08-19|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0-7619-9798-6|language=en}}</ref> The township was planned and developed with informal assistance from the city's municipal administration.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIts population rapidly increased in 1971 following the arrival of thousands of refugees fleeing from the newly-independent state of [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=\":2\" /> and the government began to regard it as a quasi-permanent settlement.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, due to its status as an unofficial and unplanned settlement,<ref>Hasan, Arif (1999) ''Akhtar Hameed Khan and the Orangi Pilot Project''. City Press, Karachi. {{ISBN|969-8380-20-5}}</ref> Orangi did not qualify for government aid or community assistance, and the area's sanitation was extremely poor.<ref name=\":6\" /> Unofficial administrators emerged and became members and leaders of local political parties.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn the 1980, as local inhabitants became frustrated at the lack of assistance from the municipal administration, the [[Orangi Pilot Project]] was launched under the guidance of [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2014/03/15/remembering-dr-akhtar-hameed-khan/|title=Remembering Dr Akhtar Hameed Khan - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref> in which the local community financed, designed and built their own low-cost sewerage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/urbanupgrading/upgrading/case-examples/ce-PK-ora.html|title=ORANGI PILOT PROJECT|website=web.mit.edu}}</ref> As a result of sense of ownership, maintain and clear the sewer system and streets themselves.<ref name=\":2\" /> Piped water was only introduced to the settlement in 1984,<ref name=\":4\" /> though the [[Karachi Water and Sewerage Board]] eventually began providing water supply to the settlement.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nUntil the early 1980s, most of Orangi's population was [[Muhajir people|Muhajir,]] or Punjabi. The towns demography began to shift in the 1980s as Pashtuns began arriving in the city in large numbers. In 1985, Karachi's ethnic divisions reached Orangi, as Muhajir and Pashtun groups fought over the area near [[Banaras Chowk|Benaras Chowk]] and Metro Cinema.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Gayer|first=Laurent|date=2003|title=A DIVIDED CITY\n\u201cETHNIC\u201d AND \u201cRELIGIOUS\u201d CONFLICTS\nIN KARACHI, PAKISTAN1|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/ceri/sites/sciencespo.fr.ceri/files/artlg.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In December 1986, [[Qasba Aligarh massacre|Pashtun gunmen attacked the Aligarh Colony]], which was home to a vulnerable population of Biharis who had recently been repatriated from Bangladesh.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThe municipality was described in a 1999 [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] article on [[Mumbai]]'s [[Dharavi]] slum as the \"largest shanty town in Asia.\"<ref name=\"nationalgeographic\" /> Orangi is in fact a lower class settlement with basic amenities of life available to most of the people. Only some parts of Orangi Town can be characterized as a slum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> At 22 square miles in size, it is \u201csignificantly less dense than most urban slums and also more structured\u201d - in comparison, Asia\u2019s next largest shanty town, [[Dharavi]] in [[Mumbai]] is home to one million people in about one single square mile.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.com/5-biggest-slums-world-381338 5 biggest slums in the world] Daniel Tovrov, IB Times (December 9, 2011)</ref> 90% of Orangi's streets are connected to sewage services. 96% of homes in Orangi have their own private latrine or toilet,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slums-pakistan-sewage-idUSKCN12D1PK|title=Fed up with no sewers, Pakistan's slum residents go DIY|date=2016-10-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live|language=en|quote=96 percent of the settlement\u2019s 112,562 households have latrines, with residents footing the total bill for the sewage system of 132,026,807 Pakistani rupees ($1.26 million).}}</ref> compared to Dharavi where there is roughly one toilet per 1,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d4d6a4d79454464776c6d636a4e6e62684a4856/share_p.html|title=Building the BRICS: Immigrants often live in informal settlements in India|last=|first=|date=|website=news.cgtn.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01|quote=Architect Samidha Patil from urbz is working currently on building public toilets and supplying water for them through wells that have never been used. Dharavi has 1 toilet block per 1000 resident.}}</ref> Most homes in Orangi feature 2 to 3 rooms.<ref name=\":2\" />  \n\nIn 2001, Orangi was formally organized and established as a proper part of the city of Karachi and granted its own Town Council.<ref name=\":3\" /> By 2004, over 90% of households in Orangi were connected to the city' electric grid, although up to 20% of connections were illegal.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n== Geography ==\nOrangi stretches out from the [[Khasba Hills]], [[North Nazimabad]] and [[Paposh Nagar]] towards the northern parts of [[Karachi]] and covers approximately 22 square miles of land. The [[Khasba Hills]] forms a natural boundary between Orangi Town and [[North Nazimabad Town]]. The [[City District Government of Karachi|City District Government]] has constructed a road through the [[Khasba Hills]] connecting Orangi Town with [[North Nazimabad Town]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jang.com.pk/|title=Daily Jang Urdu News - Pakistan News - Latest News - Breaking News|website=jang.com.pk}}</ref> \n\n== Demography ==\nOrangi's population alone is estimated to be over one million, while when combined with neighboring Baldia, the population is over 2 million.<ref name=\":3\" /> 25% of Orangi's population is [[Pashtuns]], and another 25% [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]].<ref name=\":8\" /> A significant population of [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]]s are [[Bihari people|Biharis]] who migrated from [[Bihar]] in [[partition of India|1947]], and from [[East Pakistan]] in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|1971]].<ref name=\"Bihari Orangi Town\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zX9CAAAAYAAJ&q=orangi+town+bihar&dq=orangi+town+bihar&cd=1|title=Corpses or rights (by J\u012bl\u0101n\u012b C\u0101ndp\u016br\u012b, Vaj\u0101hat \u1e24usain \u1e62idd\u012bq\u012b \u02bbAlv\u012b Q\u0101dr\u012b|publisher=Halqa-e-Alvia|quote=It was during those days i.e. before 1986 that a public meeting was held in a locality inhabited by refugees from [[Bihar]] \u2013 Orangi Town Bihar colony of...|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\"Jang-Orangi Town\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jang.com.pk/thenews/oct2009-weekly/nos-18-10-2009/kol.htm#1|title=The quest for Bihari identity|publisher=[[Daily Jang]]|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> The remaining 50% of a mix of [[Afghans in Pakistan|Afghans]], [[Baloch people|Balochis,]] [[Bengalis in Pakistan|Bengalis,]] [[Punjabi people|Punjabis]], and [[Sindhi people|Sindhis]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Orangi Pilot Project ==\n{{Main|Orangi Pilot Project}}\nOrangi poverty alleviation project ([[Orangi Pilot Project]], OPP) was initiated by [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]] in 1980. The project was aimed at socio-economic development of Orangi.<ref>Axinn, George H (1997) Book Review. ''Agriculture and Human Values'', Vol. 14, No. 2, (June). ISSN 0889-048X p. 193</ref> The project comprises a number of programs, including a people's financed and managed Low-Cost [[Sanitation]] Program;<ref>Khan, Akhtar Hameed (1997) ''[http://www.unicef.org/pon97/water1.htm The sanitation gap: Development's deadly menace]''. [http://www.unicef.org/pon97/mainmenu.htm The Progress of Nations]. [[UNICEF]]</ref> a [[House|Housing]] Program that assisted in construction of 93,000 houses<ref name=\":3\" />; a [[List of basic health topics|Basic Health]] and [[Family Planning]] Program; and a [[Rural development]] Program in the nearby villages.<ref>Khan (1996)</ref> The OPP also helps provide education services, and as a result, the literacy rate in Orangi is actually higher than the rate in Karachi over all.<ref name=\":3\" /> Along with the Orangi Charitable Trust (OCT),<ref name=\":3\" /> OPP operates a program of [[Microcredit|Supervised Credit]] for Small Family Enterprise Units. \n\nThe OPP sewer pipes are financed, constructed, and maintained by the families who live on each street,<ref name=\":2\" /> and on average cost one eighth of the cost of services provided by the municipal government.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=Inam|first=Aseem|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ru4AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA238&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwBHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Designing Urban Transformation|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-00639-6|language=en}}</ref> Pipes are built under the street, with each household contributing $800-$1000 towards construction of sewer services.<ref name=\":9\" /> \"Lane Managers\" collect dues from households, and arbitrate disputes.<ref name=\":9\" /> The OPP model has been exported to other cities in [[Sindh]] and [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab.]]<ref name=\":2\" /> OPP has also helped establish ''awami tanks,''  which are underground water cisterns for use in a local area. Many are located under Orangi's mosques and churches.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Localities within Orangi ==\n[[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]]\n* [[City District Government Karachi]]\n* [[Karachi Health and Social Development Association]]\n* [[Khasa Hills]]\n* [[Orangi Charitable Trust]]\n* [[Orangi Nala]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project Society]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project]]\n* [[Orangi Research and Training Institute]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.orangitown.com Orangi Website]\n\n{{Orangi Town}}\n{{Orangi topics}}\n\n{{coord|24|57|N|66|58|E|display=title|region:PK_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Orangi Town| ]]\n[[Category:Squats in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "\u201e\u201d{{Use Pakistani English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                     = Orangi|native_name=<br>{{nq|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u06cc}}\n|settlement_type          =  [[Municipality]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline            = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = OrangiTown Karachi.PNG\n|map_caption              = Union councils of Orangi Town\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = [[Pakistan]]\n|subdivision_type1        = Province\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Sindh]]\n|subdivision_type2        = City District\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Karachi]]\n|parts_type               = Union Councils\n|parts_style              = coll,para\n|parts                    = 13\n|p1                       = [[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />\n[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          = Town Council\n|leader_title             = Former Town Nazim\n|leader_name              = Abdul Haq\n|leader_title1            = Former Naib Nazim\n|leader_name1             = Shahid Bashir\n|leader_title2            = Municipal Officer\n|leader_name2             = Qamaruddin Shaikh\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 14 August 2001\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude           = 1 E+6\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 22\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_note          =\n|population_total         =1540420\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone                 = \n|utc_offset               = \n|timezone_DST             = \n|utc_offset_DST           = \n|latd= |latm= |lats= |latNS=\n|longd= |longm= |longs= |longEW=\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type         =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code              =\n|area_code                =\n|website                  = [http://125.209.91.254/CDGK/LinkClick.aspx?link=217&tabid=72 Orangi Town Page]\n| blank_name             = Office Location\n| blank_info             = Municipal Head Office Orangi Town No. 12, Karachi.\n| blank1_name             = E-mail\n| blank1_info             = orangi@karachicity.gov.pk\n| blank2_name             = Contact\n| blank2_info             = (021)36697869-36650833\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Orangi Town''' ({{lang-sd|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u064a \u067d\u0627\u0624\u0646}}, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u064f\u0648\u0631\u0646\u06af\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646}}}}), often referred to simply as '''Orangi''', is a borough approximately 22 square miles in area that forms much of the northwestern part of [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]. When grouped with the neighboring municipality of [[Baldia Town]], the Orangi-Baldia population is estimated to be over two million.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasan|first=Arif|date=|title=The Case of Karachi, Pakistan|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Karachi.pdf|journal=|publisher=University College London|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The municipality was described in a 1999 [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] article on [[Mumbai]]'s [[Dharavi]] slum as the \"largest shanty town in Asia.\"<ref name=\"nationalgeographic\">{{cite web|url=http://seabed.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/index.html|title=National Geographic: Dharavi, Mumbai's Shadow City|publisher=}}</ref> Orangi is in fact largely a lower to lower middle class settlement, and only some parts of Orangi Town can be characterized as a slum,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jacobson-text?fs=seabed.nationalgeographic.com|title=National Geographic Magazine|date=|publisher=Ngm.nationalgeographic.com|accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[[:File:Principaux Bidonvilles.png#Raw data]]</ref> with most homes featuring 2 to 3 rooms.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slums-pakistan-sewage-idUSKCN12D1PK|title=Fed up with no sewers, Pakistan's slum residents go DIY|date=2016-10-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> While Orangi is Karachi's largest largely unplanned settlement,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Satterthwaite|first=David|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hwWjv1vmED8C&pg=PA37&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwCXoECAgQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Water and Sanitation|date=2003|publisher=IIED|isbn=978-1-84369-479-3|language=en}}</ref> much of Orangi does receive municipal services. 90% of its streets are connected to sewage lines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1245044/karachis-orangi-town-named-largest-slum-world/|title=Karachi's Orangi Town named largest slum in the world|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2016-11-26|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/10/these-are-the-worlds-five-biggest-slums/|title=These are the world's five biggest slums|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> for example, mostly through the community-installed [[Orangi Pilot Project]], while 96% of homes have their own private latrine or toilet.<ref name=\":2\" /> Over 90% of households in Orangi are connected to Karachi's electric grid.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Wignaraja|first=Ponna|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tg_5PJYFuW8C&pg=RA9-PA5&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwixqtrAocjoAhUEt54KHYa4DDw4ChDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Pro-Poor Growth and Governance in South Asia: Decentralization and Participatory Development|last2=Sirivardana|first2=Susil|date=2004-08-19|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0-7619-9798-6|language=en}}</ref> \n\nOrangi is bordered by [[New Karachi Town]] to the north across the Shahrah-e-Zahid Hussain, [[Gulberg Town, Karachi|Gulberg Town]] to the east across the [[Gujjar Nala]] stream, [[Liaquatabad Town]] to the south, and [[SITE Town]] to the west. There are 13 official neighborhoods, each with its own council, which has allowed the township to build its own sewer system.  \n\n== History ==\nFollowing Pakistan's independence, with a large influx of refugees from India moving into Karachi. The Pakistani government by 1950 began granting permission for refugees to settle on vacant land.<ref name=\":2\" /> Orangi was established as a townshp in this context by 1965.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Inam|first=Aseem|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ru4AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA238&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwBHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Designing Urban Transformation|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-135-00639-6|location=|pages=194|language=en}}</ref> Orangi Township was originally planned over 1,300 acres by the [[Karachi Development Authority]], and many of Karachi's squatter settlements were subsequently relocated here.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Wignaraja|first=Ponna|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tg_5PJYFuW8C&pg=RA9-PA5&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwixqtrAocjoAhUEt54KHYa4DDw4ChDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Pro-Poor Growth and Governance in South Asia: Decentralization and Participatory Development|last2=Sirivardana|first2=Susil|date=2004-08-19|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0-7619-9798-6|language=en}}</ref> The township was planned and developed with informal assistance from the city's municipal administration.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIts population rapidly increased in 1971 following the arrival of thousands of refugees fleeing from the newly-independent state of [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=\":2\" /> and the government began to regard it as a quasi-permanent settlement.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, due to its status as an unofficial and unplanned settlement,<ref>Hasan, Arif (1999) ''Akhtar Hameed Khan and the Orangi Pilot Project''. City Press, Karachi. {{ISBN|969-8380-20-5}}</ref> Orangi did not qualify for government aid or community assistance, and the area's sanitation was extremely poor.<ref name=\":6\" /> Unofficial administrators emerged and became members and leaders of local political parties.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn the 1980, as local inhabitants became frustrated at the lack of assistance from the municipal administration, the [[Orangi Pilot Project]] was launched under the guidance of [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2014/03/15/remembering-dr-akhtar-hameed-khan/|title=Remembering Dr Akhtar Hameed Khan - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref> in which the local community financed, designed and built their own low-cost sewerage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/urbanupgrading/upgrading/case-examples/ce-PK-ora.html|title=ORANGI PILOT PROJECT|website=web.mit.edu}}</ref> As a result of sense of ownership, maintain and clear the sewer system and streets themselves.<ref name=\":2\" /> Piped water was only introduced to the settlement in 1984,<ref name=\":4\" /> though the [[Karachi Water and Sewerage Board]] eventually began providing water supply to the settlement.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nUntil the early 1980s, most of Orangi's population was [[Muhajir people|Muhajir,]] or Punjabi. The towns demography began to shift in the 1980s as Pashtuns began arriving in the city in large numbers. In 1985, Karachi's ethnic divisions reached Orangi, as Muhajir and Pashtun groups fought over the area near [[Banaras Chowk|Benaras Chowk]] and Metro Cinema.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Gayer|first=Laurent|date=2003|title=A DIVIDED CITY\n\u201cETHNIC\u201d AND \u201cRELIGIOUS\u201d CONFLICTS\nIN KARACHI, PAKISTAN1|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/ceri/sites/sciencespo.fr.ceri/files/artlg.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In December 1986, [[Qasba Aligarh massacre|Pashtun gunmen attacked the Aligarh Colony]], which was home to a vulnerable population of Biharis who had recently been repatriated from Bangladesh.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThe municipality was described in a 1999 [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] article on [[Mumbai]]'s [[Dharavi]] slum as the \"largest shanty town in Asia.\"<ref name=\"nationalgeographic\" /> Orangi is in fact a lower class settlement with basic amenities of life available to most of the people. Only some parts of Orangi Town can be characterized as a slum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> At 22 square miles in size, it is \u201csignificantly less dense than most urban slums and also more structured\u201d - in comparison, Asia\u2019s next largest shanty town, [[Dharavi]] in [[Mumbai]] is home to one million people in about one single square mile.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.com/5-biggest-slums-world-381338 5 biggest slums in the world] Daniel Tovrov, IB Times (December 9, 2011)</ref> 90% of Orangi's streets are connected to sewage services. 96% of homes in Orangi have their own private latrine or toilet,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-slums-pakistan-sewage-idUSKCN12D1PK|title=Fed up with no sewers, Pakistan's slum residents go DIY|date=2016-10-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live|language=en|quote=96 percent of the settlement\u2019s 112,562 households have latrines, with residents footing the total bill for the sewage system of 132,026,807 Pakistani rupees ($1.26 million).}}</ref> compared to Dharavi where there is roughly one toilet per 1,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d4d6a4d79454464776c6d636a4e6e62684a4856/share_p.html|title=Building the BRICS: Immigrants often live in informal settlements in India|last=|first=|date=|website=news.cgtn.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01|quote=Architect Samidha Patil from urbz is working currently on building public toilets and supplying water for them through wells that have never been used. Dharavi has 1 toilet block per 1000 resident.}}</ref> \n\nIn 2001, Orangi was formally organized and established as a proper part of the city of Karachi and granted its own Town Council.<ref name=\":3\" /> By 2004, over 90% of households in Orangi were connected to the city' electric grid, although up to 20% of connections were illegal.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n== Geography ==\nOrangi stretches out from the [[Khasba Hills]], [[North Nazimabad]] and [[Paposh Nagar]] towards the northern parts of [[Karachi]] and covers approximately 22 square miles of land. The [[Khasba Hills]] forms a natural boundary between Orangi Town and [[North Nazimabad Town]]. The [[City District Government of Karachi|City District Government]] has constructed a road through the [[Khasba Hills]] connecting Orangi Town with [[North Nazimabad Town]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jang.com.pk/|title=Daily Jang Urdu News - Pakistan News - Latest News - Breaking News|website=jang.com.pk}}</ref> \n\n== Demography ==\nOrangi's population alone is estimated to be over one million, while when combined with neighboring Baldia, the population is over 2 million.<ref name=\":3\" /> 25% of Orangi's population is [[Pashtuns]], and another 25% [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]].<ref name=\":8\" /> A significant population of [[Muhajir people|Muhajir]]s are [[Bihari people|Biharis]] who migrated from [[Bihar]] in [[partition of India|1947]], and from [[East Pakistan]] in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|1971]].<ref name=\"Bihari Orangi Town\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zX9CAAAAYAAJ&q=orangi+town+bihar&dq=orangi+town+bihar&cd=1|title=Corpses or rights (by J\u012bl\u0101n\u012b C\u0101ndp\u016br\u012b, Vaj\u0101hat \u1e24usain \u1e62idd\u012bq\u012b \u02bbAlv\u012b Q\u0101dr\u012b|publisher=Halqa-e-Alvia|quote=It was during those days i.e. before 1986 that a public meeting was held in a locality inhabited by refugees from [[Bihar]] \u2013 Orangi Town Bihar colony of...|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\"Jang-Orangi Town\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jang.com.pk/thenews/oct2009-weekly/nos-18-10-2009/kol.htm#1|title=The quest for Bihari identity|publisher=[[Daily Jang]]|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> The remaining 50% of a mix of [[Afghans in Pakistan|Afghans]], [[Baloch people|Balochis,]] [[Bengalis in Pakistan|Bengalis,]] [[Punjabi people|Punjabis]], and [[Sindhi people|Sindhis]].<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Orangi Pilot Project ==\n{{Main|Orangi Pilot Project}}\nOrangi poverty alleviation project ([[Orangi Pilot Project]], OPP) was initiated by [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]] in 1980. The project was aimed at socio-economic development of Orangi.<ref>Axinn, George H (1997) Book Review. ''Agriculture and Human Values'', Vol. 14, No. 2, (June). ISSN 0889-048X p. 193</ref> The project comprises a number of programs, including a people's financed and managed Low-Cost [[Sanitation]] Program;<ref>Khan, Akhtar Hameed (1997) ''[http://www.unicef.org/pon97/water1.htm The sanitation gap: Development's deadly menace]''. [http://www.unicef.org/pon97/mainmenu.htm The Progress of Nations]. [[UNICEF]]</ref> a [[House|Housing]] Program that assisted in construction of 93,000 houses<ref name=\":3\" />; a [[List of basic health topics|Basic Health]] and [[Family Planning]] Program; and a [[Rural development]] Program in the nearby villages.<ref>Khan (1996)</ref> The OPP also helps provide education services, and as a result, the literacy rate in Orangi is actually higher than the rate in Karachi over all.<ref name=\":3\" /> Along with the Orangi Charitable Trust (OCT),<ref name=\":3\" /> OPP operates a program of [[Microcredit|Supervised Credit]] for Small Family Enterprise Units. \n\nThe OPP sewer pipes are financed, constructed, and maintained by the families who live on each street,<ref name=\":2\" /> and on average cost one eighth of the cost of services provided by the municipal government.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=Inam|first=Aseem|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ru4AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA238&dq=orangi&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCw63Bm8joAhVVo54KHW3ADXEQ6AEwBHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=orangi&f=false|title=Designing Urban Transformation|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-00639-6|language=en}}</ref> Pipes are built under the street, with each household contributing $800-$1000 towards construction of sewer services.<ref name=\":9\" /> \"Lane Managers\" collect dues from households, and arbitrate disputes.<ref name=\":9\" /> The OPP model has been exported to other cities in [[Sindh]] and [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab.]]<ref name=\":2\" /> OPP has also helped establish ''awami tanks,''  which are underground water cisterns for use in a local area. Many are located under Orangi's mosques and churches.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Localities within Orangi ==\n[[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]]\n* [[City District Government Karachi]]\n* [[Karachi Health and Social Development Association]]\n* [[Khasa Hills]]\n* [[Orangi Charitable Trust]]\n* [[Orangi Nala]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project Society]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project]]\n* [[Orangi Research and Training Institute]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.orangitown.com Orangi Website]\n\n{{Orangi Town}}\n{{Orangi topics}}\n\n{{coord|24|57|N|66|58|E|display=title|region:PK_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Orangi Town| ]]\n[[Category:Squats in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Alishernavoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orangi_Town"}
{"title_page": "Ron DeSantis", "text_new": "{{short description|NOTHING HE\u2019S DONE NOTHING LATELY TO PROTECT HIS RESIDENCE. 46th governor of Florida}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Ron DeSantis\n| image         = Gov_Ron_DeSantis_Portrait.jpg <!-- consensus is needed for a replacement -->\n| order         = 46th [[List of governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]\n| lieutenant    = [[Jeanette N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]\n| term_start    = January 8, 2019\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Rick Scott]]\n| successor     = \n| state1        = [[Florida]]\n| district1     = {{ushr|FL|6|6th}}\n| term_start1   = January 3, 2013\n| term_end1     = September 10, 2018\n| predecessor1  = [[Cliff Stearns]]\n| successor1    = [[Michael Waltz]]\n| birth_name    = Ronald Dion DeSantis\n| birth_date    = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1978|9|14}}}}\n| birth_place   = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Casey DeSantis|Casey Black]]|2010}}\n| children      = 3\n| residence     = [[Florida Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n| serviceyears  = 2004\u20132010 (Active)<br/>2010\u2013present (Reserve)\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO4|25}} [[Lieutenant Commander]]\n| unit          = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| battles       = [[Iraq War]]\n| education     = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| mawards       = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br/>[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]]<br/>[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]<br/>[[File:Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n}}\n\n'''Ronald Dion DeSantis''' (born September 14, 1978) is an American attorney, naval officer, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician. He has served as the 46th [[List of governors of Florida|governor of Florida]] <!-- \"https://writingexplained.org/ap-style/ap-style-governor\" should be lowercase per MOS:JOBTITLES, kindly get consensus on talk page if you feel otherwise. --> since January 8, 2019, and he represented {{ushr|FL|6}} in Congress from 2013 to 2018. After graduating from [[Yale University]] and [[Harvard Law School]], DeSantis served as an officer and attorney in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy]] (JAG).\n\nDeSantis was a candidate in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|Florida's 2016 U.S. Senate election]], but withdrew when incumbent senator [[Marco Rubio]] announced that he would seek re-election. DeSantis then opted to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat and was re-elected. An ally of President [[Donald Trump]], DeSantis made frequent criticisms of Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election, urging Trump to shut down or significantly limit the investigation and \"suggesting agents should have briefed the Trump campaign about their efforts to investigate certain aides.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/02/gowdy-trump-spygate-theory-617948|title=Trump allies gang up on Gowdy|work=Politico|access-date=June 2, 2018|quote=Rep. Ron DeSantis (R-Fla.), a top Trump ally seeking to undermine the ongoing Russia probes}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Primary election|primary]] for [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|governor of Florida]]. On September 10, 2018, DeSantis resigned from his seat in the House of Representatives to focus on his gubernatorial campaign. DeSantis was officially certified as the winner of the [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|general election]] on November 20, 2018, following a machine recount, defeating Democratic nominee and mayor of [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] [[Andrew Gillum]]. At age {{age|1978|9|14}}, DeSantis is the [[List of current United States governors by age|youngest incumbent governor]] of a [[U.S. state]].\n\nDeSantis implemented various reforms in regards to the [[Environment of Florida|environment]], [[drug policy reform|drug policy]], and the state [[budget]]; he allocated $2.5 billion for water resource projects including $360 million for [[Everglades]] projects,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/29/desantis-reveals-spending-plan-for-everglades-fixes/|title=DeSantis reveals spending plan for Everglades fixes|last=Gross|first=Samantha J.|date=January 29, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> urged the legislature to support the use of smokeable [[medical cannabis]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/17/on-medical-marijuana-florida-gov-ron-desantis-wants-to-heed-the-will-of-voters/|title=On medical marijuana, Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis wants to heed the will of voters|last=Gross|first=Samantha J.|date=January 17, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>, and supported budget increases<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/11/18/desantis-budget-1-billion-on-teacher-raises-millions-for-elections-security/|title=DeSantis budget: $1 billion on teacher pay, millions for elections security|date=November 8, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Early life and education==\nRonald Dion DeSantis was born on September 14, 1978, in [[Jacksonville, Florida]], the son of Karen (Rogers) and Ronald DeSantis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://obittree.com/obituary/us/florida/palm-harbor/curlew-hills-memory-gardens-inc/christina-desantis/2164525/ |title=Christina Marie DeSantis Obituary - Palm Harbor, FL|website=Obittree.com}}</ref> His family moved to [[Orlando, Florida]], before relocating to [[Dunedin, Florida]], when he was 6 years old.<ref>[http://saintpetersblog.com/ron-desantis-admits-gop-faithful-are-demoralized-depressed-and-dejected-at-d-c-republicans/]</ref> In 1991 he was a member of the [[Little League]] team from Dunedin National that went on from the regular season to the [[Little League World Series]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Fall Elections Shape Future Rosters |url=http://www.rollcall.com/features/Baseball-Program_2012/baseball/Fall-Elections-Shape-Future-Rosters-215692-1.html |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vaccaro|first1=Ron|title=Baseball's DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Yale News|date=March 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating in 1997 from [[Dunedin High School]] in Dunedin, Florida, DeSantis attended [[Yale University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in history in 2001.<ref>https://news.yale.edu/2014/11/05/seventeen-yale-alumni-won-congressional-governors-races-election-day-2014</ref> While at Yale, he was also captain of the varsity baseball team,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams/|title=Baseball\u2019s DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|first1=Ron Vaccaro 12:00|last1=am|first2=|last2=Mar 30|first3=|last3=2001|website=yaledailynews.com}}</ref> and a brother of [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]], joining the same chapter that once counted [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[George W. Bush]] as members. After Yale, he then joined [[Darlington School]] serving on the Upper School history department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.darlingtonschool.org/2460189|title=Darlington School: Darlington welcomes new faces|website=Darlington School}}</ref> He then attended [[Harvard Law School]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/137630/ron-desantis|title=Ron DeSantis' Biography \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nDeSantis received his [[United States Navy Reserve|Reserve Naval officer's commission]] and assignment to Judge Advocate General's Corps (JAG) in 2004 at the U.S. Naval Reserve Center in [[Dallas]], Texas, while still a student at Harvard Law School. He completed [[Naval Justice School|U.S. Naval Justice School]] in 2005. Later that year, he received orders to the Trial Service Office Command South East at the [[Naval Station Mayport]], Florida, as a [[military justice|JAG prosecutor]]. In 2006, he was promoted from [[Lieutenant Junior Grade|lieutenant junior grade]] (LTJG) to lieutenant (LT). He worked for the [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo|commander of Joint Task Force-Guantanamo]] (JTF-GTMO), working directly with detainees at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay Joint Detention Facility]].<ref name=\"congress-bio\">{{cite web|url=https://desantis.house.gov/about|title=About|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925054202/https://desantis.house.gov/about|archive-date=September 25, 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-082918>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article217545910.html|title=Who is Ron DeSantis, the Republican running for Florida governor? |work=[[The Miami Herald]]|last=Mahoney|first=Emily|date=August 29, 2018|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-081418>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article216615190.html |title=This candidate for Florida governor cites serving at Guant\u00e1namo. What did he do there?|work=[[The Miami Herald]] |last=Mahoney|date=August 14, 2018|first=Emily|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\t\nIn 2007, DeSantis reported to the [[Naval Special Warfare Command]] Group in [[Coronado, California]], where he was assigned to [[SEAL Team One]] and deployed to [[Iraq War of 2003|Iraq]]<ref name=farrington>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brenda|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=May 27, 2016|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref> with the [[Iraq troop surge|troop surge]] as the Legal Advisor to the SEAL Commander, Special Operations Task Force-West in [[Fallujah]].<ref name=congress-bio/><ref name=Mahoney-082918/><ref name=Mahoney-081418/>\n\t\nHe returned to the United States in April 2008, at which time he was reassigned to the Naval Region Southeast Legal Service. He was appointed by the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] to serve as a [[federal prosecutor]]<ref name=farrington/> at the [[U.S. Attorney for the Middle District of Florida|U.S. Attorney's Office in the Middle District of Florida]]. DeSantis was assigned as a trial defense counsel until his honorable discharge from active duty in February 2010. He concurrently accepted a reserve commission as a lieutenant in the Judge Advocate General Corps of the [[US Navy Reserve]].<ref name=wsj/> He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]], the [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]], the [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]] and the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]].<ref name=congress-bio/><ref name=Mahoney-082918/><ref name=Mahoney-081418/>\n\n==Writing==\nHe authored a book entitled ''Dreams From Our Founding Fathers: First Principles in the Age of Obama'', which was published in 2011.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis (R)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/ron-desantis--FL-H|accessdate=May 27, 2016|work=Election 2012}}</ref> His writing has appeared in ''[[National Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', ''[[Human Events]]'', and ''[[American Thinker]]''.<ref name=wsj/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Florida#District 6}}\nIn 2012, DeSantis announced he would run in the Republican primary for the 6th District. The district had previously been the [[Florida's 7th congressional district|7th]], represented by 10-term Republican [[John Mica]]. However, Mica's share of Orlando had been drawn into the new 7th District, and Mica opted to run there even though the new 6th included the bulk of his former territory.\n\nDeSantis won the six-candidate Republican primary with 39% of the vote, with the runner-up, state representative [[Fred Costello]], obtaining 23%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=756561|title=FL District 06 \u2013 R Primary Race |date=August 14, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref> In the November general election, DeSantis defeated Democratic candidate [[Heather Beaven]] by 57\u201343%, with majorities in all four counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=736113|title=FL District 06 Race|date=November 6, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPrior to the [[114th United States Congress]], DeSantis was named the chairman of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security|Subcommittee on National Security]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Despite Opposing 'CRomnibus,' Sophomore Ron DeSantis Ascends Congressional Ladder|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/despite-opposing-cromnibus-sophomore-ron-desantis-ascends-congressional-ladder|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 29, 2014, DeSantis introduced into the House the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=3972sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3972 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3973 |publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week |accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> DeSantis spoke in favor of the bill, arguing that \"President Obama has not only failed to uphold several of our nation's laws, he has vowed to continue to do so in order to enact his unpopular agenda. ...The American people deserve to know exactly which laws the Obama administration is refusing to enforce and why.\"<ref name=\"HtargetsObamalawEnf\"/> The bill did not subsequently become law.\n\nIn 2013, DeSantis signed a pledge sponsored by the Libertarian PAC founded by billionaires [[Charles Koch]] and [[David Koch]], [[Americans for Prosperity]], promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf |title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Ron DeSantis|accessdate=October 8, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015194819/http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf |archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2017, DeSantis added a [[rider (legislation)|rider]] to the proposed fiscal 2018 spending bill package that would end funding for the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|Mueller investigation]] \"or for the investigation under that order of matters occurring before June 2015\" ([[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections#June\u2013December 2015|the month Trump announced he was running for president]]) 180 days after passage of the bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/348343-gop-lawmaker-proposes-amendment-that-would-stop-funding-for-special-counsel|title=GOP lawmaker proposes amendment to stop Mueller investigation after 180 days|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|author=Shelbourne, Mallory|date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> The amendment was intended to counter a bipartisan bill written by two Democratic and two Republican U.S. senators, which was intended to limit the president's power to fire the special counsel. The DeSantis amendment sought to cut off funding for the investigation by November 2017. It was also a response to Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]]'s statement that the [[United States Department of Justice|DOJ]], \"doesn't conduct [[fishing expedition]]s.\" DeSantis stated that the May 17, 2017 DOJ order \"didn't identify a crime to be investigated and practically invites a fishing expedition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108|title=Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months|work=[[Politico]]|author=Wright, Austin |date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> In fact, however, Rosenstein appointed the Special Council \"after a cascade of damaging developments for Mr. Trump...including his abrupt dismissal of the F.B.I. director, James B. Comey, and the subsequent disclosure that Mr. Trump asked Mr. Comey to drop the investigation of his former national security adviser, Michael T. Flynn.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/17/us/politics/robert-mueller-special-counsel-russia-investigation.html|title=Robert Mueller, Former F.B.I. Director, Is Named Special Counsel for Russia Investigation|last=Ruiz and Landler|first=Rebecca R. and Mark|date=May 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was a founding member of the [[Freedom Caucus]], a group of congressional conservatives and libertarians.<ref name=\"Mahoney-081418\"/><ref name=\"Contorno-180810\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/08/10/ron-desantis-wants-to-lead-florida-through-hurricanes-he-voted-against-helping-sandy-victims/ |title=Ron DeSantis wants to lead Florida through hurricanes. He voted against helping Sandy victims.|work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |first=Steve |last=Contorno}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it?|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==2016 U.S. Senate candidacy==\n{{main|2016 United States Senate election in Florida}}\nOn May 6, 2015, DeSantis announced that he was running for the [[United States Senate]] seat held by [[Marco Rubio]], who initially did not file to run for re-election due to [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign, 2016|his bid]] for the [[U.S. presidency]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Letitia|title=Florida Congressman Ron DeSantis running for U.S. Senate |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/06/us-usa-election-florida-senate-idUSKBN0NR1S420150506|accessdate=May 7, 2015 |agency=Reuters|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> He was endorsed by the fiscally conservative [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Video: Club for Growth backs DeSantis|url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/241205-video-club-for-growth-backs-desantis |accessdate=June 3, 2015|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis withdrew and instead campaigned for re-election to the House once Rubio entered the Senate race after ending his presidential bid.\n\n==Governor of Florida==\n[[File:Trump and DeSantis.jpg|thumb|right|DeSantis and his wife, Casey, with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Melania Trump]] in February 2019]]\n\n===Election===\n{{main|2018 Florida gubernatorial election}}\nIn January 2018, DeSantis announced his candidacy for [[governor of Florida]] to succeed term-limited Republican incumbent [[Rick Scott]]. President Donald Trump stated in December 2017 that he would support DeSantis should he run for governor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrington|first=Brendan|url=https://apnews.com/2bea559f0e1e4e1dbbaf79775ab35471|title=Trump's tweeted choice for Florida governor enters the race|work=[[Associated Press]] News|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> During the Republican primary, DeSantis emphasized his support for Trump by running an ad where DeSantis taught his children how to \"build the wall\" and say \"Make America Great Again\" and by dressing one of his children in a tiny red \"Make America Great Again\" jumper.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/07/30/new-lighthearted-ron-desantis-ad-features-his-family-trump-jokes/ |title=New lighthearted Ron DeSantis ad features his family, Trump jokes|last=Mahoney|first=Emily|work=Tampa Bay Times |accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Asked if he could name an issue where he disagreed with Trump, DeSantis did not identify a single issue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/30/us/politics/florida-governor-election.html|title=In Florida, Not All Politics Are Local, as Trump Shapes Governor's Race|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> On July 30, 2018, [[Jonathan Martin (journalist)|Jonathan Martin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that the support DeSantis's primary campaign had received demonstrated both Trump's kingmaking capacity in a Republican-trending state but also a \"broader nationalization of conservative politics\" wherein \"a willingness to hurl rhetorical lightning bolts at the left, the media and special counsel Robert S. Mueller can override local credentials, local endorsements and preparedness for a state-based job.\"<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the Republican primary. His [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent in the [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|general election]] was [[Andrew Gillum]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/28/us/politics/florida-arizona-election-results.html|title=Andrew Gillum, a Black Progressive, and Ron DeSantis, a Trump Acolyte, Win Florida Governor Primaries|date=August 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref> The race was \"widely seen as a toss-up\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/gop-florida-governor-nominee-ron-desantis-criticized-for-monkey-remark/|title=GOP Florida governor nominee Ron DeSantis criticized for \"monkey\" remark|publisher=CBS News|date=August 29, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, DeSantis announced state representative [[Jeanette N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] as his running mate.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180906/andrew-gillum-ron-desantis-select-running-mates|title=Andrew Gillum, Ron DeSantis select running mates|last=Kennedy|first=John|work=Jacksonville.com|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref> He resigned his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives on September 10, 2018, to focus on his gubernatorial candidacy.<ref name=Moe-180910>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/rep-ron-desantis-resigns-congress-n908146 |title=Amid heated governor's race, Ron DeSantis resigns from Congress |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=September 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 10, 2018 |first=Alex |last=Moe |first2=Rebecca |last2=Shabad |first3=Ali |last3=Vitali}}</ref> That same month, DeSantis was criticized for not having a fully formed policy platform for his gubernatorial campaign.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/09/13/morning-joe-mocks-ron-desantis-for-ducking-tough-questions-on-florida-issues/|title=Morning Joe mocks Ron DeSantis for ducking tough questions on Florida issues|last=Contorno|first=Steve|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> He cancelled a planned interview with the ''Tampa Bay Times'' to have additional time to put together a platform before an in-depth policy interview.<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\nDeSantis was endorsed by the Florida Police Chiefs Association in his 2018 campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/279614-police-chiefs-ron-desantis|title=Thin blue line goes red: Police chiefs backing Ron DeSantis|website=FloridaPolitics.com|date=October 31, 2018}}</ref> In the campaign, some sheriffs endorsed DeSantis, while other sheriffs backed Gillum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/2018/10/16/ron-desantis-florida-sheriffs/1658174002/|title=4 Florida sheriffs, including Brevard County's Wayne Ivey, back Ron DeSantis|website=Florida Today}}</ref>\n\n====Platform====\nDeSantis's gubernatorial platform includes support for legislation that would allow persons with concealed weapons permits to carry firearms openly.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-governor-race-desantis-gillum-issues-20180831-story.html|title=Florida governor's race: Where Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues |work=Orlando Sentinel|last=Rohrer|first=Gray|date=August 31, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> He also supports a law mandating the use of [[E-Verify]] by businesses and a state-level ban on [[sanctuary city]] protections for undocumented immigrants.<ref name=\"auto\"/> DeSantis has promised to stop the spread of polluted water from [[Lake Okeechobee]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> DeSantis has also expressed support for a state constitutional amendment to require a supermajority vote for any tax increases.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=August 31, 2018|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> He opposes allowing able-bodied, childless adults to receive Medicaid.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> DeSantis has stated that he would implement a medical marijuana program, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"floridapolitics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/267561-ron-desantis-gets-solid-hits-on-national-issues-in-fox-news-debate|title=Ron DeSantis gets solid hits on national issues in Fox News debate - Florida Politics |website=Floridapolitics.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.wfsu.org/post/putnam-desantis-find-common-ground-opposing-recreational-pot|title=Putnam, DeSantis Find Common Ground Opposing Recreational Pot|first=Ryan|last=Dailey|website=News.wfsu.org|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====\"Monkey this up\" controversy====\nOn August 29, 2018, DeSantis came under criticism for comments that were allegedly racist, saying, \"The last thing we need to do is to monkey this up by trying to embrace a socialist agenda with huge tax increases and bankrupting the state. That is not going to work. That's not going to be good for Florida.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/desantis-under-fire-saying-florida-should-t-monkey-electing-gillum-n904746|title=DeSantis under fire for saying Florida shouldn't 'monkey this up' by electing Gillum, who is black|publisher=NBC News|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis was accused of using the verb \"monkey\" as a [[Dog-whistle politics|racist dog whistle]]; his opponent, Gillum, was African-American.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/29/us/politics/desantis-monkey-up-gillum.html|title=DeSantis Warns Florida Not to 'Monkey This Up,' and Many Hear a Racist Dog Whistle|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|date=August 29, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> Amid the controversy over DeSantis' comments, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Naples Daily News]]'' reported that DeSantis had on four occasions appeared at racially-charged conferences at the [[David Horowitz Freedom Center]] that featured various right-wing provocateurs as speakers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/gop-candidate-for-fla-governor-spoke-at-racially-charged-events/2018/09/09/c6d3a63c-b114-11e8-a810-4d6b627c3d5d_story.html|title=GOP candidate for Fla. governor spoke at racially charged events|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://eu.naplesnews.com/story/news/politics/2018/06/22/ron-desantis-accepted-luxury-hotel-stay-attend-right-wing-event/723598002/|title=DeSantis attended convention with speakers who have suggested killing Muslims, demeaned women|work=Naples Daily News|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis stated that his comment had \"zero to do with race\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/404355-desantis-monkey-comment-has-zero-to-do-with-race|title=DeSantis: 'Monkey' comment has 'zero to do with race'|work=TheHill.com|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=August 30, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Results ====\nInitial election-night results had DeSantis winning by nearly 100,000 votes, and Gillum conceded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/11/06/florida-governor-election-results-andrew-gillum-versus-ron-desantis/|title=Florida governor election results: Andrew Gillum versus Ron DeSantis|last=Wilson|first=Kirby|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> Gillum took back his concession as late-counted ballots brought the race within less than 34,000 votes, a margin of 0.4%. The close margin required an automatic machine recount of the ballots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/10/gillum-reverses-course-on-conceding-florida-governor-race.html|title=Gillum reverses course on conceding Florida governor race|date=2018-11-10|website=Cnbc.com|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\nA machine recount in three statewide contests (governor, [[2018 United States Senate election in Florida|U.S. senator]], and [[Florida Commissioner of Agriculture|agriculture commissioner]]) began with a deadline of November 15, 2018. Although three counties missed the deadline, it was not extended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/15/florida-recount-ron-desantis-prevails-over-andrew-gillum-governor/2006942002/|title=With Florida recount over, Andrew Gillum's last chance to become governor rests with the courts|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/416945-florida-senate-race-heads-to-a-hand-recount|title=Florida Senate race heads to a hand recount|last=Nam|first=Rafael|date=2018-11-15|website=TheHill.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> DeSantis was confirmed as the winner and Gillum conceded on November 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/17/politics/gillum-concedes-florida-governors-race-desantis/index.html|title=Andrew Gillum concedes Florida governor's race to Ron DeSantis|author1=Dan Merica|author2=Sophie Tatum|website=Cnn.com|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDeSantis prefiled the oath of office with the Florida Secretary of State and became governor at midnight, January 8, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/05/desantis-already-governor-when-ceremony-begins/|title=DeSantis already governor when ceremony begins|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]}}</ref> The official swearing in ceremony was held at noon that day. On January 11, 2019, DeSantis posthumously pardoned the [[Groveland Four]], four black men falsely convicted of rape in 1949.<ref name=\"ReasonGroveland\">{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Zuri |title=70 Years After They Were Wrongly Imprisoned, the Groveland Four Have Been Pardoned |url=https://reason.com/blog/2019/01/11/groveland-four-pardoned-after-70-years |website=Reason.com |accessdate=11 January 2019 |date=11 January 2019}}</ref> That same day, DeSantis officially suspended [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] [[sheriff]] [[Scott Israel]] for his response to the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]].\n\nIn his first two weeks in office, DeSantis appointed [[Barbara Lagoa]], [[Robert J. Luck]] and [[Carlos G. Mu\u00f1iz]] to fill the three vacancies on the [[Florida Supreme Court]], shifting the court from having a liberal to a conservative majority. He replaced the entire South Florida Water Management District board. He signed $2.5 billion executive order for water quality and Everglades restoration work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/political-roundtable-gov-desantis-actions-so-far-tampa-mayoral-race-gets-crowded-more|title=Political Roundtable: Gov. DeSantis&#039; Actions So Far, Tampa Mayoral Race Gets Crowded &amp; More|website=Wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu}}</ref> He created a [[Chief Science Officer|chief science officer]] position and created an office of coastal protection and resilience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/weekly-roundup-flexing-some-executive-muscle|title=Weekly Roundup: Flexing Some Executive Muscle|first=Dara Kam News Service of|last=Florida|date=January 11, 2019|website=Sunshinesstatenews.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, DeSantis signed an executive order calling for the end of [[Common Core]] in Florida.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Patrick | first1=Craig | title=Florida Gov. DeSantis signs executive order scrapping Common Core | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/florida-gov-desantis-signs-executive-order-scrapping-common-core | date=January 31, 2019 | publisher=[[Fox News]] (from [[WTVT]]) | accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis encouraged Florida sheriffs to cooperate with the federal government on immigration-related issues.<ref>{{cite web | title=Sheriffs look at options amid DeSantis immigration push | url=https://www.winknews.com/2019/03/12/sheriffs-look-at-options-amid-desantis-immigration-push/ | date=March 12, 2019 | publisher=[[WINK-TV]] | accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, DeSantis signed an anti-[[sanctuary city]] bill that requires law enforcement \"to honor U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement detainers for undocumented immigrants who are arrested or convicted\" of crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/advocates-say-florida-governor-sanctuary-bill-politically-motivated-n1017976|title=Advocates say Florida governor's 'sanctuary bill' politically motivated|website=NBC News|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ron-desantis-florida-sanctuary-immigration_n_5d03e0aae4b0985c419d439f|title=Florida Governor Signs Bill Banning Sanctuary Policies|date=June 14, 2019|website=HuffPost|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/florida-de-santis-signs-controversial-sanctuary-cities|title=Florida's DeSantis signs controversial sanctuary cities ban into law|first=Sam|last=Dorman|date=June 14, 2019|website=Fox News|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article231552873.html</ref> Florida became the 12th state to ban sanctuary cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/florida-becomes-th-state-to-ban-sanctuary-cities/article_a7382e03-4b84-5a79-a04b-f583959f7b5a.html|title=Florida becomes 12th state to ban sanctuary cities|first=Catherine E.|last=Shoichet|website=FOX Carolina|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, DeSantis signed a measure that would make it harder to launch successful ballot initiatives. Petition-gathering for ballot initiatives to legalize medical marijuana, increases to the minimum wage, and expansion of Medicaid were also under way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/06/07/ron-desantis-signs-crack-down-on-constitutional-amendments-solidifying-republican-control-in-florida/|title=Ron DeSantis signs crack down on constitutional amendments, solidifying Republican control in Florida|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://miami.cbslocal.com/2019/06/06/ballot-initiatives-measure-goes-to-florida-governor-ron-desantis/|title=Ballot Initiatives Measure Goes To Florida Governor Ron Desantis|date=2019-06-06|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/06/09/gov-desantis-signs-hb5-eviscerating-the-democratic-process-in-florida|title=Gov. DeSantis signs HB5, 'eviscerating' the democratic process in Florida|last=Florida|first=Jim Saunders, News Service of|website=Orlando Weekly|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, following on the heels of a 2018 constitutional amendment referendum in favor of voting rights restoration for felons, DeSantis signed legislation that restricted such restoration only to those felons who had fully paid back all fees and fines to the courts, a move that was criticized despite being in line with what the authors of the 2018 amendment has wanted in ''[[The New York Times]]'' as reminiscent of [[Poll taxes in the United States|poll taxes]] in the [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow]] South and prompted a lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/us/florida-felons-voting-rights.html|title=Florida Limits Ex-Felon Voting, Prompting a Lawsuit and Cries of \u2018Poll Tax\u2019|last=Mazzei|first=Patricia|date=2019-06-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn August&nbsp;28, 2019, DeSantis declared a state of emergency for 26 counties in [[Hurricane Dorian]]'s expected path.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/08/28/governor-ron-desantis-declares-state-of-emergency-urges-floridians-to-prepare-for-hurricane-dorian/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis Declares State of Emergency, Urges Floridians to Prepare for Hurricane Dorian|publisher=Government of Florida|date=August 28, 2019|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> This later expanded to the entire state on August&nbsp;29.\n\nIn March 2020 DeSantis decided against declaring a state of emergency in [[Florida]] during the [[Corona pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-update-governor-ron-desantis-calls-for-major-disaster-declaration-for-florida/ar-BB11E0A4|title=Coronavirus Update: Governor Ron DeSantis Calls For Major Disaster Declaration For Florida|publisher=MSN News|date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/25/gov-ron-desantis-wont-shut-down-florida-heres-who-hes-talking-to-about-that|title=Gov. Ron DeSantis won\u2019t shut down Florida. Here\u2019s who he\u2019s talking to about that.\n|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|date=March, 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Representative Ron DeSantis, Iran's Missile Program (17983165814).jpg|thumbnail|right|DeSantis speaking at the Hudson Institute in June 2015]]\nDeSantis is a conservative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2017/12/22/trump-endorses-desantis-for-governor-via-twitter-161236|title=Trump endorses DeSantis for governor via Twitter|work=Politico PRO|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/05/07/404805852/meet-the-tea-partys-new-favorite-candidate|title=Meet The Tea Party's New Favorite Candidate|publisher=NPR|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/ron-desantis-tea-party-favorite-becomes-first-republican-to-enter-senate-race-7597712|title=Ron DeSantis, Tea Party Favorite, Becomes First Republican to Enter Senate Race|last=Munzenrieder|first=Kyle|date=May 6, 2015|work=Miami New Times|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> He was endorsed by the [[Family Research Council Action PAC]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac |title=Ron DeSantis endorsed by Common Core opponent FRC Action PAC|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|date=November 23, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Orlando Political Observer|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125162156/http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac|archivedate=November 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Marijuana ===\nDeSantis supports the implementation of a medical marijuana program in Florida, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"floridapolitics.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gainesville.com/news/20180601/legalizing-cannabis-divides-candidates-for-governor|title=Legalizing cannabis divides candidates for governor|first=George Bennett Palm Beach|last=Post|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> He voted against the Veterans Equal Access Amendment that would give veterans access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.safeaccessnow.org/veteran_2017_blumenauer|title=2016 Congressional Scorecard|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Contraceptives and abortion ===\nDeSantis [[Opposition to abortion|opposes abortion]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424801/planned-parenthood-chief-abortion-survivor-baby-entitled-medical-care-joel-gehrke|title=Planned Parenthood Head: An Abortion Survivor is a 'Baby' Entitled to Medical Care|last1=Gehkre|first1=Joel|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=National Review}}</ref> and has denounced [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/186587-ron-desantis-denounces-planned-parenthoods-loathsome-practice|title=Ron DeSantis denounces Planned Parenthood's alleged \"loathsome practice\" |last1=Gancarski|first1=A.G.|date=July 15, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis agreed with the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.]]'', saying \"This case does not concern the availability or legality of contraceptives, and individuals can obtain and use these as they see fit. The question is simply whether the government can force the owners of Hobby Lobby to pay for abortifacients in violation of their faith.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/florida-congressmen-divide-over-hobby-lobby-case|title=Florida Congressmen Divide Over Hobby Lobby Case|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy ===\nDeSantis has said that the debate in Washington, D.C., over how to reduce the deficit should shift emphasis from tax increases to curtailing spending and triggering economic growth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Douglas|title=DeSantis emphasizes importance of economic growth|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2012-12-15/desantis-economic-growth-essential |accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=December 16, 2012}}</ref> He supports a \"no budget no pay\" policy for Congress to encourage the passage of a budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wexler|first1=Gene|title=New St. Johns Rep. opens up on financial and governmental reforms|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/news/local/new-st-johns-rep-opens-financial-and-governmental-/nTmcb |accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=WOKV|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> He believes the [[Federal Reserve System]] should be audited.<ref name=roll/>\n\nIn the wake of the alleged [[IRS targeting controversy]], DeSantis called for the resignation of Internal Revenue Service commissioner [[John Koskinen]] for having \"failed the American people by frustrating Congress's attempts to ascertain the truth.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Jordan|first2=Jim|title=The Stonewall at the Top of the IRS|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-stonewall-at-the-top-of-the-irs-1438039060|accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Mitch|title=Ron DeSantis wants Obama to remove IRS commissioner\u2014or else |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187207-ron-desantis-wants-obama-to-remove-irs-commissioner-or-else|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 28, 2015}}</ref> He co-sponsored a bill to impeach Koskinen for violating the public's trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oversight.house.gov/release/resolution-introduced-impeach-irs-commissioner|title=Resolution Introduced to Impeach IRS Commissioner|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=House Oversight Committee|date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, DeSantis was named \"Taxpayer Superhero\" by [[Citizens Against Government Waste]], a conservative think-tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gancarski|first1=July 31, 2015|title=Email insights: Ron DeSantis, \"Taxpayer Superhero\" |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187434-email-insights-ron-desantis-taxpayer-superhero|accessdate=February 28, 2016 |publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supported the [[Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act|Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny (REINS) Act]], which would require that regulations that have a significant economic impact be subject to a vote of Congress prior to taking effect.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siefring|first1=Neil|title=The REINS Act will keep regulations and their costs in check |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/economy-budget/250178-the-reins-act-will-keep-regulations-and-their-costs-in |accessdate=February 28, 2016|newspaper=The Hill|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis introduced the [[Let Seniors Work Act]], which would repeal the [[Earnings test (US)|Retirement Earnings Test]] and exempt senior citizens from the 12.4% [[Federal Insurance Contributions Act tax|Social Security payroll tax]], and he co-sponsored a measure to eliminate taxes on [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin |title=Marco Rubio, Ron DeSantis Restore 'Let Seniors Work Act'|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/marco-rubio-ron-desantis-restore-let-seniors-work-act|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis sponsored the Transportation Empowerment Act, which would transfer much of the responsibility for transportation projects to the individual states and sharply reduce the [[federal gas tax]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laing|first1=Keith|title=Bill filed to sharply reduce the gas tax|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/244597-bill-filed-to-eliminate-the-gas-tax|accessdate=February 28, 2016|newspaper=The Hill|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Mike|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Economy Commentary Let America Fix the Highways Washington Broke|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/10/let-america-fix-the-highways-washington-broke|accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Daily Signal|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis has opposed legislation to require online retailers to collect and pay state sales tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dixon |first1=Matt|title=Retail group assails DeSantis over Internet sales tax|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2013-06-27#.VtONM_HvOac|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122017\">{{cite news|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah |title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> DeSantis says the bill will bring a \"dramatically lower tax rate\" and \"full expensing of capital investments.\" DeSantis also believes the act will bring more jobs to America.<ref name=\"Brown121917\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Stephanie|title=Northeast Florida lawmakers divided on impact of tax reform plan |website=Wokv.com|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/local/northeast-florida-lawmakers-divided-impact-gop-tax-reform-plan/vyBF5BQ8kPldHOvKT0JGdK/|publisher=WOKV Radio|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nDeSantis opposes federal education programs such as [[No Child Left Behind Act]] and [[Race to the Top]], saying that education policy should be made at the local level.<ref name=roll>{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis, R-Fla. (6th District) |url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/ron-desantis-house-r-fla-6.html|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis introduced the [[Higher Education Reform and Opportunity Act]], which would allow states to create their own accreditation systems. In an op-ed for the ''[[National Review]]'', DeSantis said that his legislation would give students \"access to federal loan money to put towards non-traditional educational opportunities, such as online learning courses, vocational schools, and apprenticeships in skilled trades.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Lee|first2=Mike|title=Break Up the Higher-Ed Cartel|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/414848/break-higher-ed-cartel-ron-desantis-mike-lee|accessdate=February 29, 2016 |work=National Review|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign relations===\n[[File:President Trump Delivers Remarks to the Venezuelan-American Community (47096114742).jpg|thumb|DeSantis watches as President [[Donald Trump]] delivers remarks to the [[Venezuelan Americans|Venezuelan American]] community in February 2019]]\n\n====Cuba====\nIn 2015, DeSantis introduced the Guantanamo Bay Recidivism Prevention Act, which would cut off foreign aid to countries that receive detainees if they show back up on the terrorism recidivism list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis: Releasing Guantanamo Detainees is a Security Threat|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/ron-desanits-releasing-guantanamo-detainees-security-threat|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis opposed [[Barack Obama|President Obama]]'s plan to shut down the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]], saying \"Bringing hardened terrorists to the U.S. homeland harms our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Obama's GITMO Proposal Draws Fire From GOP Candidates Vying to Replace Marco Rubio|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/obamas-gitmo-propsoal-draws-fire-gop-candidates-vying-replace-marco-rubio|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the formal restart of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and Cuba, DeSantis said \"Raising the Cuban flag in the United States is a slap in the face to those who have experienced the brutality of the Castro regime.\"<ref name=reaction>{{cite news |last1=Leary|first1=Alex|title=Florida reaction to Cuba news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/florida-reaction-to-cuba-news/2237995|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nDeSantis opposed the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]], calling it \"a bad deal that will significantly degrade our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotton|first1=Tom|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Congress Must Reject the Iran Deal |url=http://time.com/3978510/congress-must-reject-the-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Time|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis said \"the Iran deal gives Ayatollah Khamenei exactly what he wants: billions of dollars in sanctions relief, validation of the Iranian nuclear program, and the ability to stymie inspections.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeSantis Condemns Deal as a Gift to Iran's Ayatollah|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/desantis-condemns-deal-as-a-gift-to-irans-ayatollah |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a line of questioning, DeSantis told Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] that the executive branch had a legal obligation to provide Congress with the details behind any side deals made between world leaders and Iran.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank |title=DeSantis and Kerry get contentious over Iran Deal|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/07/29/desantis-and-kerry-get-contentious-over-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Orlando Political Observer|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis accused President Barack Obama of giving better treatment of Cuba's [[Raul Castro]] and Iran's Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] than of Israel's [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=save>{{cite news|last1=Man|first1=Anthony|title='We need to save the country', conservative U.S. Senate candidate tells Broward activists|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ron-desantis-conservative-candidate-20150824-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nIn 2013, DeSantis introduced the Palestinian Accountability Act, which would halt U.S. aid to the [[Palestinian National Authority|Palestinian Authority]] until it formally recognizes [[Israel]]'s right to exist as a Jewish state and cuts off all ties with the militant group [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kredo|first1=Adam|title=House Bill Would Cut Aid to Palestinian Authority |url=http://freebeacon.com/national-security/house-bill-would-cut-aid-to-palestinian-authority|accessdate=February 26, 2016 |work=Washington Free Beacon|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis co-introduced the Non-Discrimination of Israel in Labeling Act, which will defend the right of Israeli producers to label products manufactured in the West Bank as \"Israel,\" \"Made in Israel,\" or \"Product of Israel.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganckarski |first1=A.G.|title=Ron DeSantis co-introduces non-discrimination of Israel in labeling act |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/201890-ron-desantis-co-introduces-non-discrimination-of-israel-in-labeling-act |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis supported the move of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/05/13/scott-desantis-in-israel-for-u-s-embassy-opening/ |title=Scott, DeSantis in Israel for U.S. Embassy opening |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=May 13, 2018 |accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs governor, in light of [[Airbnb]]'s decision to no longer allow rentals of [[Israeli settlement]]s in the [[West Bank]], on January 15, 2019, DeSantis directed the Department of Management Services to no longer reimburse state employees and state contractors for travel expenses incurred with Airbnb;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/01/15/governor-ron-desantis-announces-actions-to-affirm-floridas-support-of-israel/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis Announces Actions to Affirm Florida's Support of Israel|website=Flgov.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> later that month he accepted the recommendation of the State Board of Administration to place Airbnb on Florida's \"Scrutinized Companies List\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/01/29/governor-ron-desantis-statement-on-cabinet-decision-placing-airbnb-on-scrutinized-companies-list/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis' Statement on Cabinet Decision Placing Airbnb on Scrutinized Companies List|website=Flgov.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Government===\nDeSantis opted not to receive his [[congressional pension]], and he filed a measure that would eliminate pensions for members of Congress.<ref name=roll/> After introducing the End Pensions in Congress Act, DeSantis said \"The Founding Fathers envisioned elected officials as part of a servant class, yet Washington has evolved into a ruling class culture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harper |first1=Jennifer|title=No more 'ruling class culture': New legislation would jettison pensions for Congress |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/2/no-more-ruling-class-culture-new-legislaiton-would/|accessdate=February 28, 2016 |work=The Washington Times|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supports a constitutional amendment to impose [[term limit]]s for members of Congress, so that representatives would be limited to three terms and senators to two terms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brendan|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html |accessdate=February 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gun law===\nDeSantis opposes [[gun control]]. He received an A+ rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keller |first1=Michael|title=This is Your Representative on Guns |url=http://thedailybeast.thisisyourreponguns.com/#Pane=overview&Chamber=House|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Daily Beast |date=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\nHe is generally opposed to firearm regulation, saying, \"Very rarely do firearms restrictions affect criminals. They really only affect law-abiding citizens.\"<ref name=\"Maddock 2013\">{{cite news| title=Ron DeSantis Put On Spot By Sandy Hook Parents At Florida Town Hall |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/20/ron-desantis-sandy-hook_n_2726089.html|last=Maddock|first=Preston |date=February 20, 2013 |work=HuffPost |accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2018 [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in [[Parkland, Florida]], DeSantis expressed his support for hiring retired [[law enforcement officer]]s and military [[veteran]]s as armed guards for schools.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\">{{cite news |last=Bennett |first=George |date=February 20, 2018 |title=Ron DeSantis: Enlist retired military, cops to prevent school shootings |url=http://postonpolitics.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2018/02/20/ron-desantis-enlist-retired-military-cops-to-prevent-school-shootings/ |work=The Palm Beach Post |location=Palm Beach, Florida |access-date=February 23, 2018 }}</ref> He disagrees with legislation signed into law by Florida governor Rick Scott that banned bump stocks, added a mandatory three-day waiting period for gun purchases, and raised the legal age for purchases from 18 to 21.<ref name=Mahoney-082918/> He has expressed support for measures to improve federal background checks for purchasing firearms and has said that there is a need to intervene with those who are exhibiting warning signs of committing violence instead of waiting until a crime has been committed.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\"/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nDeSantis is opposed to the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"Repeal\">{{cite press release|title=Rep. DeSantis Statement on ObamaCare Repeal|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-desantis-statement-on-obamacare-repeal |publisher=Office of Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Moorhead|first1=Molly |title=Florida Rep. Ron DeSantis says 'Obamacare' tax is cheaper than insurance|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/jan/24/ron-desantis/desantis-says-obamacare-tax-cheaper-insurance/|accessdate=February 27, 2016 |publisher=PolitiFact|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He has called for the \"full and complete repeal\" of the act.<ref name=\"Repeal\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, DeSantis said that he wasn't ready to support the [[American Health Care Act]], the House Republican effort to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tony Perry|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gops-darrell-issa-represents-a-clear-test-for-anti-trump-democrats-trying-for-electoral-gains-in-2018/2017/03/11/5d20b0f0-05ed-11e7-ad5b-d22680e18d10_story.html|title=GOP's Darrell Issa represents a clear test for anti-Trump Democrats trying for electoral gains in 2018 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> He did vote for the May 2017 Republican effort to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2018/09/10/democrats-launch-website-attacking-desantiscare-600996|title=Democrats launch website attacking 'DeSantisCare'|work=Politico PRO|access-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html |title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill|last=Aisch|first=Gregor|access-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of March 2020, Florida had 6,741 confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|covid-19]], however DeSantis would not issue a statewide \u201cstay-at-home\u201d order because the Trump administration had not recommended that he do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/04/01/coronavirus-florida-desantis/|title=Florida covid-19 cases surge to nearly 7,000 as Ron DeSantis resists statewide restrictions|date=April 1, 2020|author=Barbash, Fred|accessdate=April 1, 2020|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> Then on April 1, DeSantis ordered that all Floridians stay home for 30 days with exceptions for essential services and activities.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rohrer, Gray and Lemongello, Steven|date=April 1, 2020|title=DeSantis announces statewide shutdown order for Florida through April|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/os-ne-coronavirus-desantis-wednesday-20200401-yc2ttrxuw5hx7ci3zn2id3ynlq-story.html|accessdate=April 1, 2020|publisher=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nDeSantis was a critic of President Obama's immigration policies; he opposed Obama's deferred action programs ([[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA) and [[Deferred Action for Parents of Americans]] (DAPA) and accused him of failing to enforce immigration laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/ron-desantis-turns-heat-obama-failing-enforce-immigration-laws |title=Ron DeSantis Turns Up the Heat on Obama for Failing to Enforce Immigration Laws|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/17/before-skeptical-lawmakers-officials-defend-legality-of-obamas-immigration-actions|title=Before Skeptical Lawmakers, Officials Defend 'Legality' of Obama's Immigration Actions|last1=Scanlon|first1=Kate|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Daily Signal}}</ref> DeSantis opposes \"sanctuary cities.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/4358373421001/sanctuary-cities-under-fire-/?#sp=show-clips|title=\u2190 Shrink player Sanctuary cities under fire|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016 |publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref> He is a co-sponsor of the Establishing Mandatory Minimums for Illegal Reentry Act of 2015, also known as Kate's Law, which would amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to increase penalties applicable to aliens who unlawfully reenter the United States after being removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trackbill.com/bill/us-hr3011-kates-law/1198394|title=HR3011 Kate's Law|publisher=TrackBill|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, DeSantis spoke at [[ACT! for America]], an anti-Muslim advocacy group.<ref name=-180917>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/09/17/ron-desantis-act-america-address/1333447002/ |title=Florida's Ron DeSantis spoke to group whose founder says devout Muslims can't be loyal Americans |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 17, 2018 |first=Trevor |last=Aaronson}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], DeSantis \"called for urgent recognition that Islamic extremism is to blame for the Paris attacks and should be seen as an enemy for America.\" DeSantis has said \"The enemy is an ideology rooted in militant Islam\" and has said that [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] must be stopped and its members kept away from America.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-sunshine-summit-senate-candidates-20151114-story.html|title=GOP Senate candidates call for fight against Islamic militants after Paris attacks|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref> Regarding U.S. policy toward refugees, DeSantis said \"the prudent policy is to err on the side of protecting the American people\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2015/11/27/rep-ron-desantis-on-refugee-debate-err-on-side-protecting-american-people/|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis on refugee debate: 'Err on side of protecting the American people' |date=November 27, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT issues===\nDeSantis has a \"0\" rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] based on his record of voting on [[LGBT rights|LGBT]]-related issues and legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2016/10/07/rubios-score-plummets-to-0-in-hrc-congressional-ratings |title=Rubio's score plummets to '0' in HRC congressional ratings|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|date=October 7, 2016|newspaper=[[Washington Blade]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, he told the ''Sun Sentinel'' he \"doesn't want any discrimination in Florida, I want people to be able to live their life, whether you're gay or whether you're religious.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/104830236-132.html|title=Ron DeSantis answered question on his stance on gay rights|website=Sun-Sentinel|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, less than a week after taking office, DeSantis issued a nondiscrimination order for state employees reiterating former governor [[Rick Scott|Scott]]'s order; while the order included [[race (human categorization)|race]], [[ageing|age]], [[sex]], [[ethnic group|color]], [[religion]], [[nationality|national origin]], [[marriage|marital status]] and [[disability]], it included no protections for [[sexual orientation]] or [[gender identity]]. [[Equality Florida]] strongly criticized DeSantis, with the organization's senior political director stating that Equality Florida was \"deeply disappointed to see that LGBTQ employees and contractors have been left out of the governor's executive order.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2019/01/09/new-fla-guv-excludes-lgbt-people-from-non-discrimination-order/|title=New Fla. guv excludes LGBT people from non-discrimination order|newspaper=Washington Blade|author=Chris Johnson|date=9 January 2019}}</ref> DeSantis's predecessor had pledged to sign an LGBT-inclusive order as governor, but ultimately did not follow through on the grounds that proper federal protections existed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/01/10/florida-gov-ron-desantis-excludes-lgbtq-protections-from-anti-discrimination-order|title=Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis excludes LGBTQ protections from anti-discrimination order|newspaper=Orlando Weekly|author=Monivette Cordeiro|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, DeSantis' office issued a proclamation honoring the victims of the June 12, 2016 [[Orlando nightclub shooting]] at the [[Pulse nightclub|Pulse]] [[gay bar]] and [[nightclub]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], where 49 people were killed and 50 others were injured by [[Omar Mateen]]. The proclamation did not include any reference to the LGBT community, sparking severe criticism and accusations that the governor intentionally omitted the category from the message; [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Florida House of Representatives|state representatives]] [[Anna Eskamani]] and [[Carlos Guillermo Smith]], who is openly gay, lambasted the governor, while [[gun control]] activist [[Fred Guttenberg]], whose daughter was killed in a [[school shooting]] [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|in Broward County a year earlier]], questioned if the omission was predetermined. DeSantis reissued the proclamation with revisions including mentions of the LGBT community, and a spokesperson stated that the omission was due to an error on the part of DeSantis' staff. Former Governor Scott included an LGBT reference in a prior Pulse memorial message.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2019/06/12/desantis-does-about-face-after-omitting-lgbtq-from-pulse-proclamation-1058537|title=DeSantis does about-face after omitting LGBTQ from Pulse proclamation|publisher=Politico|author=Matt Dixon, Gary Fineout|date=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Russia investigation===\nAccording to the ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'', DeSantis \"made a name for himself&nbsp;[in&nbsp;2017] attacking special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation&nbsp;into Russian meddling in the 2016 election.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/05/rep-ron-desantis-declares-run-for-florida-governor|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis declares run for Florida governor|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis proposed an amendment that would halt funding for Mueller's [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|2017 Special Counsel investigation]] probe six months after the amendment's passage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amendments-rules.house.gov/amendments/DESANT_055_xml824171651535153.pdf|title=Amendment to Division C of the Rules Committee Print 115-31 Offered by Mr. DeSantis of Florida|website=Amendments-rules.house.gov|format=PDF|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> In addition, this provision would prohibit Mueller from investigating matters that occurred before June 2015, when Trump launched his presidential campaign.<ref>Austin Wright, [http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108 Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months], Politico.com, August 28, 2017.</ref> In December 2017, DeSantis asserted that if there was any evidence of collusion between members of the Trump campaign and Russian officials, it would already have been leaked.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/366923-judiciary-republican-if-there-was-any-trump-russia-collusion-it-would-have|title=Judiciary Republican: If there was any Trump-Russia collusion, it would have leaked months ago|last=Manchester|first=Julia |date=December 31, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, while on the House Intelligence Committee, DeSantis voted on party lines to release a classified memo authored by Republicans on the committee which purported to show that the FBI abused its surveillance powers in the Russia investigation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/house-vote-releasing-classified-nunes-memo-about-fbi-eavesdropping-n842311|title=House intelligence panel votes to release classified Nunes memo about FBI eavesdropping|publisher=NBC News |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis voted not to release a memo authored by Democrats on the committee which accused the Republicans on the committee of playing politics with national security.<ref name=\":0\"/> Democrats described the Republican-authored memo as grossly distorted and intended to discredit the Mueller Special Counsel investigation, and said that the Republicans on the committee had begun an investigation into the FBI and DOJ.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, DeSantis called on FBI director [[Christopher A. Wray|Christopher Wray]] to criminally investigate a number of officials involved in investigating Russian interference in the 2016 election, including former FBI director [[James Comey]], former acting director of the FBI [[Andrew McCabe]], FBI agent [[Peter Strzok]] and FBI counsel [[Lisa Page]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/384312-trump-to-lawmakers-pressing-sessions-on-comey-good-luck-with-that|title=Trump to lawmakers pressing Sessions to investigate Comey and Clinton: 'Good luck with that'|last=Shelbourne|first=Mallory|date=April 22, 2018 |work=TheHill|access-date=April 24, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis also called for investigations of a number of former Obama officials, including [[Loretta Lynch]] and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/18/trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations-532516|title=trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2019, a spokesman for DeSantis announced that he would be \"returning a political contribution he received from two Soviet-born businessmen, [[Lev Parnas and Igor Fruman]], through their company Global Energy Producers. Parnas and Fruman are accused of funneling foreign cash into U.S. elections to increase their influence and promote their business interests; they are central figures in the Trump-Ukraine scandal and impeachment inquiry. \"They made the donation a day before Trump tweeted his 'full endorsement' of DeSantis.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-ne-campaign-finance-indictments-20191010-jwao3r2q3vd4ff3jpsprrl5azu-story.html|title=Gov. Ron DeSantis to return campaign cash from indicted South Florida businessmen with Giuliani ties|last=Swisher, Skyler|first=Chokey, Aric & Gray, Rohrer|date=October 10, 2019|work=South Florida Sun Sentinel|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans===\nDeSantis has sharply criticized the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] for the [[Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014]], in which veteran deaths were linked to wait times. He co-sponsored the VA Accountability Act, which aims to increase accountability by providing for the removal or demotion of employees of the Department of Veterans Affairs based on performance or misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winslow|first1=Hailey|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis pushes legislation to hold Veterans Affairs accountable|url=http://www.news4jax.com/news/florida/st-johns-county/congressman-ron-desantis-pushes-legislation-to-hold-veterans-affairs-accountable|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=News 4 Jax|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis |first1=Clifford|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis pushes for VA reform in St. Augustine|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/politics/2014-05-05/story/rep-ron-desantis-pushes-va-reform-st-augustine|accessdate=February 27, 2016|newspaper=[[Florida Times Union]]|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the Post-9/11 Veterans Caucus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Porter|first1=Thomas|title=IAVA Team Continues to Seek Path Forward for 9/11 First Responders|url=http://iava.org/blogs/iava-team-continues-to-seek-path-forward-for-911-first-responders-press-conference-tomorrow|publisher=Iraq & Afghanistan Veterans of America|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting rights ===\n{{As of|August 2018}}, DeSantis had not taken a position on a November 2018 ballot initiative on the restoration of voting rights for felons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/30/where-they-stand-candidates-for-governor-on-vote-for-felons/|title=Where they stand: Candidates for governor on vote for felons|last=Bousquet|first=Steve|date=January 30, 2018|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Pantazi-180824>{{cite web |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180817/floridas-prisons-are-more-expensive-than-ever-what-will-next-governor-do-about-it |title=Florida's prisons are more expensive than ever. What will the next governor do about it?|work=[[Florida Times-Union]]|date=August 24, 2018|accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Andrew|last=Pantazi}}</ref>\n\n===Law enforcement===\nDeSantis called for [[Broward County Sheriff's Office|Broward County Sheriff]] [[Scott Israel]] to resign after the Parkland school shooting committed by [[Nikolas Cruz]]. Israel was accused by a large number of people of running his department poorly and not properly handling or responding to the shooting. DeSantis stated that had he been governor when the shooting occurred he would have removed Israel from his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20181212/exclusive-desantis-to-act-quickly-on-water-supreme-court-broward-sheriff|title=EXCLUSIVE: DeSantis to act quickly on water, Supreme Court, Broward sheriff|first=George|last=Bennett|date=December 12, 2018|newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ss1112019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-ne-sheriff-israel-suspension-20190111-story.html |title=Sheriff Scott Israel: Career defined by controversy and fury over failures during Parkland shooting |last=Swisher |first=Skyler |date=January 11, 2019 |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> On January 11, shortly after taking office as governor, DeSantis suspended Israel from his duties. Israel declared that he intends to contest his suspension.<ref name=\"ss1112019\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Ron DeSantis and Casey DeSantis.jpg|thumb|Ron and Casey DeSantis in January 2019]]\nDeSantis is a [[Roman Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.cq.com/members/46138|title=RollCall.com \u2013 Member Profile \u2013 Rep. Ron DeSantis, R-Fla.|website=Media.cq.com}}</ref> and of Italian descent. In 2010, he married [[Casey DeSantis|Casey Black]]. They lived in [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida|Ponte Vedra Beach]], near [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]] until Ponte Vedra Beach was drawn into the neighboring [[Florida's 4th congressional district|4th district]]. DeSantis and his wife then moved to [[Palm Coast, Florida|Palm Coast]], north of Daytona Beach.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Harper |url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/news/20160729/congressman-ron-desantis-moves-to-flagler-county|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis moves to Flagler County|website=News-journalonline.com|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|title=Ronald Dion DeSantis \u2013 Florida Resident Database|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019033354/https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|archivedate=October 19, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis and his wife have two daughters and a son. <ref>{{cite tweet | last = DeSantis | first = Casey | user = FLCaseyDeSantis | number = 1244601703795765248 | date = 30 March 2020 | title = Ron and I are beyond blessed to welcome our new baby girl, Mamie to the world. At 7 lbs 4 oz she was the smallest of the bunch, but she is already holding her own. Madison and Mason are so excited for their new baby sister! | access-date = 30 March 2020 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.flgov.com/ official Florida Governor website]\n* [https://rondesantis.com// Campaign website]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Ron_DeSantis_%5BR-06%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rondesantis}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=D000621 |votesmart=137630 |fec=H2FL00292 |congress=ron-desantis/D000621 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cliff Stearns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Florida's 6th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Waltz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Florida]]|years=[[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Florida]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Florida}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br/>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br/>{{nowrap|''{{small|as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the US House of Representatives]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gretchen Whitmer]]|as=[[Governor of Michigan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Florida}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Greg Abbott]]|as=[[Governor of Texas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Florida}}\n{{Current Florida statewide political officials}}\n{{U.S. Governors}}\n{{U.S. Florida Representatives}}\n{{RepNomFlGov}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeSantis, Ron}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American military lawyers]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Governors of Florida]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Florida]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American conservative people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|46th governor of Florida}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Ron DeSantis\n| image         = Gov_Ron_DeSantis_Portrait.jpg <!-- consensus is needed for a replacement -->\n| order         = 46th [[List of governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]\n| lieutenant    = [[Jeanette N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]\n| term_start    = January 8, 2019\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Rick Scott]]\n| successor     = \n| state1        = [[Florida]]\n| district1     = {{ushr|FL|6|6th}}\n| term_start1   = January 3, 2013\n| term_end1     = September 10, 2018\n| predecessor1  = [[Cliff Stearns]]\n| successor1    = [[Michael Waltz]]\n| birth_name    = Ronald Dion DeSantis\n| birth_date    = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1978|9|14}}}}\n| birth_place   = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Casey DeSantis|Casey Black]]|2010}}\n| children      = 3\n| residence     = [[Florida Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n| serviceyears  = 2004\u20132010 (Active)<br/>2010\u2013present (Reserve)\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO4|25}} [[Lieutenant Commander]]\n| unit          = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| battles       = [[Iraq War]]\n| education     = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| mawards       = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br/>[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]]<br/>[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]<br/>[[File:Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n}}\n\n'''Ronald Dion DeSantis''' (born September 14, 1978) is an American attorney, naval officer, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician. He has served as the 46th [[List of governors of Florida|governor of Florida]] <!-- \"https://writingexplained.org/ap-style/ap-style-governor\" should be lowercase per MOS:JOBTITLES, kindly get consensus on talk page if you feel otherwise. --> since January 8, 2019, and he represented {{ushr|FL|6}} in Congress from 2013 to 2018. After graduating from [[Yale University]] and [[Harvard Law School]], DeSantis served as an officer and attorney in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy]] (JAG).\n\nDeSantis was a candidate in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|Florida's 2016 U.S. Senate election]], but withdrew when incumbent senator [[Marco Rubio]] announced that he would seek re-election. DeSantis then opted to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat and was re-elected. An ally of President [[Donald Trump]], DeSantis made frequent criticisms of Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election, urging Trump to shut down or significantly limit the investigation and \"suggesting agents should have briefed the Trump campaign about their efforts to investigate certain aides.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/02/gowdy-trump-spygate-theory-617948|title=Trump allies gang up on Gowdy|work=Politico|access-date=June 2, 2018|quote=Rep. Ron DeSantis (R-Fla.), a top Trump ally seeking to undermine the ongoing Russia probes}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Primary election|primary]] for [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|governor of Florida]]. On September 10, 2018, DeSantis resigned from his seat in the House of Representatives to focus on his gubernatorial campaign. DeSantis was officially certified as the winner of the [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|general election]] on November 20, 2018, following a machine recount, defeating Democratic nominee and mayor of [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] [[Andrew Gillum]]. At age {{age|1978|9|14}}, DeSantis is the [[List of current United States governors by age|youngest incumbent governor]] of a [[U.S. state]].\n\nDeSantis implemented various reforms in regards to the [[Environment of Florida|environment]], [[drug policy reform|drug policy]], and the state [[budget]]; he allocated $2.5 billion for water resource projects including $360 million for [[Everglades]] projects,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/29/desantis-reveals-spending-plan-for-everglades-fixes/|title=DeSantis reveals spending plan for Everglades fixes|last=Gross|first=Samantha J.|date=January 29, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> urged the legislature to support the use of smokeable [[medical cannabis]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/17/on-medical-marijuana-florida-gov-ron-desantis-wants-to-heed-the-will-of-voters/|title=On medical marijuana, Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis wants to heed the will of voters|last=Gross|first=Samantha J.|date=January 17, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>, and supported budget increases<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/11/18/desantis-budget-1-billion-on-teacher-raises-millions-for-elections-security/|title=DeSantis budget: $1 billion on teacher pay, millions for elections security|date=November 8, 2019|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Early life and education==\nRonald Dion DeSantis was born on September 14, 1978, in [[Jacksonville, Florida]], the son of Karen (Rogers) and Ronald DeSantis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://obittree.com/obituary/us/florida/palm-harbor/curlew-hills-memory-gardens-inc/christina-desantis/2164525/ |title=Christina Marie DeSantis Obituary - Palm Harbor, FL|website=Obittree.com}}</ref> His family moved to [[Orlando, Florida]], before relocating to [[Dunedin, Florida]], when he was 6 years old.<ref>[http://saintpetersblog.com/ron-desantis-admits-gop-faithful-are-demoralized-depressed-and-dejected-at-d-c-republicans/]</ref> In 1991 he was a member of the [[Little League]] team from Dunedin National that went on from the regular season to the [[Little League World Series]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Fall Elections Shape Future Rosters |url=http://www.rollcall.com/features/Baseball-Program_2012/baseball/Fall-Elections-Shape-Future-Rosters-215692-1.html |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vaccaro|first1=Ron|title=Baseball's DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Yale News|date=March 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating in 1997 from [[Dunedin High School]] in Dunedin, Florida, DeSantis attended [[Yale University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in history in 2001.<ref>https://news.yale.edu/2014/11/05/seventeen-yale-alumni-won-congressional-governors-races-election-day-2014</ref> While at Yale, he was also captain of the varsity baseball team,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams/|title=Baseball\u2019s DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|first1=Ron Vaccaro 12:00|last1=am|first2=|last2=Mar 30|first3=|last3=2001|website=yaledailynews.com}}</ref> and a brother of [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]], joining the same chapter that once counted [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[George W. Bush]] as members. After Yale, he then joined [[Darlington School]] serving on the Upper School history department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.darlingtonschool.org/2460189|title=Darlington School: Darlington welcomes new faces|website=Darlington School}}</ref> He then attended [[Harvard Law School]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/137630/ron-desantis|title=Ron DeSantis' Biography \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nDeSantis received his [[United States Navy Reserve|Reserve Naval officer's commission]] and assignment to Judge Advocate General's Corps (JAG) in 2004 at the U.S. Naval Reserve Center in [[Dallas]], Texas, while still a student at Harvard Law School. He completed [[Naval Justice School|U.S. Naval Justice School]] in 2005. Later that year, he received orders to the Trial Service Office Command South East at the [[Naval Station Mayport]], Florida, as a [[military justice|JAG prosecutor]]. In 2006, he was promoted from [[Lieutenant Junior Grade|lieutenant junior grade]] (LTJG) to lieutenant (LT). He worked for the [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo|commander of Joint Task Force-Guantanamo]] (JTF-GTMO), working directly with detainees at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay Joint Detention Facility]].<ref name=\"congress-bio\">{{cite web|url=https://desantis.house.gov/about|title=About|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925054202/https://desantis.house.gov/about|archive-date=September 25, 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-082918>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article217545910.html|title=Who is Ron DeSantis, the Republican running for Florida governor? |work=[[The Miami Herald]]|last=Mahoney|first=Emily|date=August 29, 2018|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-081418>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article216615190.html |title=This candidate for Florida governor cites serving at Guant\u00e1namo. What did he do there?|work=[[The Miami Herald]] |last=Mahoney|date=August 14, 2018|first=Emily|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\t\nIn 2007, DeSantis reported to the [[Naval Special Warfare Command]] Group in [[Coronado, California]], where he was assigned to [[SEAL Team One]] and deployed to [[Iraq War of 2003|Iraq]]<ref name=farrington>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brenda|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=May 27, 2016|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref> with the [[Iraq troop surge|troop surge]] as the Legal Advisor to the SEAL Commander, Special Operations Task Force-West in [[Fallujah]].<ref name=congress-bio/><ref name=Mahoney-082918/><ref name=Mahoney-081418/>\n\t\nHe returned to the United States in April 2008, at which time he was reassigned to the Naval Region Southeast Legal Service. He was appointed by the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] to serve as a [[federal prosecutor]]<ref name=farrington/> at the [[U.S. Attorney for the Middle District of Florida|U.S. Attorney's Office in the Middle District of Florida]]. DeSantis was assigned as a trial defense counsel until his honorable discharge from active duty in February 2010. He concurrently accepted a reserve commission as a lieutenant in the Judge Advocate General Corps of the [[US Navy Reserve]].<ref name=wsj/> He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]], the [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]], the [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]] and the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]].<ref name=congress-bio/><ref name=Mahoney-082918/><ref name=Mahoney-081418/>\n\n==Writing==\nHe authored a book entitled ''Dreams From Our Founding Fathers: First Principles in the Age of Obama'', which was published in 2011.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis (R)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/ron-desantis--FL-H|accessdate=May 27, 2016|work=Election 2012}}</ref> His writing has appeared in ''[[National Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', ''[[Human Events]]'', and ''[[American Thinker]]''.<ref name=wsj/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Florida#District 6}}\nIn 2012, DeSantis announced he would run in the Republican primary for the 6th District. The district had previously been the [[Florida's 7th congressional district|7th]], represented by 10-term Republican [[John Mica]]. However, Mica's share of Orlando had been drawn into the new 7th District, and Mica opted to run there even though the new 6th included the bulk of his former territory.\n\nDeSantis won the six-candidate Republican primary with 39% of the vote, with the runner-up, state representative [[Fred Costello]], obtaining 23%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=756561|title=FL District 06 \u2013 R Primary Race |date=August 14, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref> In the November general election, DeSantis defeated Democratic candidate [[Heather Beaven]] by 57\u201343%, with majorities in all four counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=736113|title=FL District 06 Race|date=November 6, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPrior to the [[114th United States Congress]], DeSantis was named the chairman of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security|Subcommittee on National Security]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Despite Opposing 'CRomnibus,' Sophomore Ron DeSantis Ascends Congressional Ladder|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/despite-opposing-cromnibus-sophomore-ron-desantis-ascends-congressional-ladder|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 29, 2014, DeSantis introduced into the House the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=3972sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3972 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3973 |publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week |accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> DeSantis spoke in favor of the bill, arguing that \"President Obama has not only failed to uphold several of our nation's laws, he has vowed to continue to do so in order to enact his unpopular agenda. ...The American people deserve to know exactly which laws the Obama administration is refusing to enforce and why.\"<ref name=\"HtargetsObamalawEnf\"/> The bill did not subsequently become law.\n\nIn 2013, DeSantis signed a pledge sponsored by the Libertarian PAC founded by billionaires [[Charles Koch]] and [[David Koch]], [[Americans for Prosperity]], promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf |title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Ron DeSantis|accessdate=October 8, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015194819/http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf |archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2017, DeSantis added a [[rider (legislation)|rider]] to the proposed fiscal 2018 spending bill package that would end funding for the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|Mueller investigation]] \"or for the investigation under that order of matters occurring before June 2015\" ([[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections#June\u2013December 2015|the month Trump announced he was running for president]]) 180 days after passage of the bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/348343-gop-lawmaker-proposes-amendment-that-would-stop-funding-for-special-counsel|title=GOP lawmaker proposes amendment to stop Mueller investigation after 180 days|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|author=Shelbourne, Mallory|date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> The amendment was intended to counter a bipartisan bill written by two Democratic and two Republican U.S. senators, which was intended to limit the president's power to fire the special counsel. The DeSantis amendment sought to cut off funding for the investigation by November 2017. It was also a response to Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]]'s statement that the [[United States Department of Justice|DOJ]], \"doesn't conduct [[fishing expedition]]s.\" DeSantis stated that the May 17, 2017 DOJ order \"didn't identify a crime to be investigated and practically invites a fishing expedition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108|title=Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months|work=[[Politico]]|author=Wright, Austin |date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> In fact, however, Rosenstein appointed the Special Council \"after a cascade of damaging developments for Mr. Trump...including his abrupt dismissal of the F.B.I. director, James B. Comey, and the subsequent disclosure that Mr. Trump asked Mr. Comey to drop the investigation of his former national security adviser, Michael T. Flynn.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/17/us/politics/robert-mueller-special-counsel-russia-investigation.html|title=Robert Mueller, Former F.B.I. Director, Is Named Special Counsel for Russia Investigation|last=Ruiz and Landler|first=Rebecca R. and Mark|date=May 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was a founding member of the [[Freedom Caucus]], a group of congressional conservatives and libertarians.<ref name=\"Mahoney-081418\"/><ref name=\"Contorno-180810\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/08/10/ron-desantis-wants-to-lead-florida-through-hurricanes-he-voted-against-helping-sandy-victims/ |title=Ron DeSantis wants to lead Florida through hurricanes. He voted against helping Sandy victims.|work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |first=Steve |last=Contorno}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it?|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==2016 U.S. Senate candidacy==\n{{main|2016 United States Senate election in Florida}}\nOn May 6, 2015, DeSantis announced that he was running for the [[United States Senate]] seat held by [[Marco Rubio]], who initially did not file to run for re-election due to [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign, 2016|his bid]] for the [[U.S. presidency]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Letitia|title=Florida Congressman Ron DeSantis running for U.S. Senate |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/06/us-usa-election-florida-senate-idUSKBN0NR1S420150506|accessdate=May 7, 2015 |agency=Reuters|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> He was endorsed by the fiscally conservative [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Video: Club for Growth backs DeSantis|url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/241205-video-club-for-growth-backs-desantis |accessdate=June 3, 2015|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis withdrew and instead campaigned for re-election to the House once Rubio entered the Senate race after ending his presidential bid.\n\n==Governor of Florida==\n[[File:Trump and DeSantis.jpg|thumb|right|DeSantis and his wife, Casey, with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Melania Trump]] in February 2019]]\n\n===Election===\n{{main|2018 Florida gubernatorial election}}\nIn January 2018, DeSantis announced his candidacy for [[governor of Florida]] to succeed term-limited Republican incumbent [[Rick Scott]]. President Donald Trump stated in December 2017 that he would support DeSantis should he run for governor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrington|first=Brendan|url=https://apnews.com/2bea559f0e1e4e1dbbaf79775ab35471|title=Trump's tweeted choice for Florida governor enters the race|work=[[Associated Press]] News|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> During the Republican primary, DeSantis emphasized his support for Trump by running an ad where DeSantis taught his children how to \"build the wall\" and say \"Make America Great Again\" and by dressing one of his children in a tiny red \"Make America Great Again\" jumper.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/07/30/new-lighthearted-ron-desantis-ad-features-his-family-trump-jokes/ |title=New lighthearted Ron DeSantis ad features his family, Trump jokes|last=Mahoney|first=Emily|work=Tampa Bay Times |accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref> Asked if he could name an issue where he disagreed with Trump, DeSantis did not identify a single issue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/30/us/politics/florida-governor-election.html|title=In Florida, Not All Politics Are Local, as Trump Shapes Governor's Race|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> On July 30, 2018, [[Jonathan Martin (journalist)|Jonathan Martin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that the support DeSantis's primary campaign had received demonstrated both Trump's kingmaking capacity in a Republican-trending state but also a \"broader nationalization of conservative politics\" wherein \"a willingness to hurl rhetorical lightning bolts at the left, the media and special counsel Robert S. Mueller can override local credentials, local endorsements and preparedness for a state-based job.\"<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the Republican primary. His [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent in the [[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|general election]] was [[Andrew Gillum]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/28/us/politics/florida-arizona-election-results.html|title=Andrew Gillum, a Black Progressive, and Ron DeSantis, a Trump Acolyte, Win Florida Governor Primaries|date=August 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref> The race was \"widely seen as a toss-up\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/gop-florida-governor-nominee-ron-desantis-criticized-for-monkey-remark/|title=GOP Florida governor nominee Ron DeSantis criticized for \"monkey\" remark|publisher=CBS News|date=August 29, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, DeSantis announced state representative [[Jeanette N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] as his running mate.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180906/andrew-gillum-ron-desantis-select-running-mates|title=Andrew Gillum, Ron DeSantis select running mates|last=Kennedy|first=John|work=Jacksonville.com|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref> He resigned his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives on September 10, 2018, to focus on his gubernatorial candidacy.<ref name=Moe-180910>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/rep-ron-desantis-resigns-congress-n908146 |title=Amid heated governor's race, Ron DeSantis resigns from Congress |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=September 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 10, 2018 |first=Alex |last=Moe |first2=Rebecca |last2=Shabad |first3=Ali |last3=Vitali}}</ref> That same month, DeSantis was criticized for not having a fully formed policy platform for his gubernatorial campaign.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/09/13/morning-joe-mocks-ron-desantis-for-ducking-tough-questions-on-florida-issues/|title=Morning Joe mocks Ron DeSantis for ducking tough questions on Florida issues|last=Contorno|first=Steve|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> He cancelled a planned interview with the ''Tampa Bay Times'' to have additional time to put together a platform before an in-depth policy interview.<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\nDeSantis was endorsed by the Florida Police Chiefs Association in his 2018 campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/279614-police-chiefs-ron-desantis|title=Thin blue line goes red: Police chiefs backing Ron DeSantis|website=FloridaPolitics.com|date=October 31, 2018}}</ref> In the campaign, some sheriffs endorsed DeSantis, while other sheriffs backed Gillum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/2018/10/16/ron-desantis-florida-sheriffs/1658174002/|title=4 Florida sheriffs, including Brevard County's Wayne Ivey, back Ron DeSantis|website=Florida Today}}</ref>\n\n====Platform====\nDeSantis's gubernatorial platform includes support for legislation that would allow persons with concealed weapons permits to carry firearms openly.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-governor-race-desantis-gillum-issues-20180831-story.html|title=Florida governor's race: Where Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues |work=Orlando Sentinel|last=Rohrer|first=Gray|date=August 31, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> He also supports a law mandating the use of [[E-Verify]] by businesses and a state-level ban on [[sanctuary city]] protections for undocumented immigrants.<ref name=\"auto\"/> DeSantis has promised to stop the spread of polluted water from [[Lake Okeechobee]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> DeSantis has also expressed support for a state constitutional amendment to require a supermajority vote for any tax increases.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=August 31, 2018|accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> He opposes allowing able-bodied, childless adults to receive Medicaid.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> DeSantis has stated that he would implement a medical marijuana program, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"floridapolitics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/267561-ron-desantis-gets-solid-hits-on-national-issues-in-fox-news-debate|title=Ron DeSantis gets solid hits on national issues in Fox News debate - Florida Politics |website=Floridapolitics.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.wfsu.org/post/putnam-desantis-find-common-ground-opposing-recreational-pot|title=Putnam, DeSantis Find Common Ground Opposing Recreational Pot|first=Ryan|last=Dailey|website=News.wfsu.org|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====\"Monkey this up\" controversy====\nOn August 29, 2018, DeSantis came under criticism for comments that were allegedly racist, saying, \"The last thing we need to do is to monkey this up by trying to embrace a socialist agenda with huge tax increases and bankrupting the state. That is not going to work. That's not going to be good for Florida.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/desantis-under-fire-saying-florida-should-t-monkey-electing-gillum-n904746|title=DeSantis under fire for saying Florida shouldn't 'monkey this up' by electing Gillum, who is black|publisher=NBC News|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis was accused of using the verb \"monkey\" as a [[Dog-whistle politics|racist dog whistle]]; his opponent, Gillum, was African-American.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/29/us/politics/desantis-monkey-up-gillum.html|title=DeSantis Warns Florida Not to 'Monkey This Up,' and Many Hear a Racist Dog Whistle|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|date=August 29, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> Amid the controversy over DeSantis' comments, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Naples Daily News]]'' reported that DeSantis had on four occasions appeared at racially-charged conferences at the [[David Horowitz Freedom Center]] that featured various right-wing provocateurs as speakers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/gop-candidate-for-fla-governor-spoke-at-racially-charged-events/2018/09/09/c6d3a63c-b114-11e8-a810-4d6b627c3d5d_story.html|title=GOP candidate for Fla. governor spoke at racially charged events|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://eu.naplesnews.com/story/news/politics/2018/06/22/ron-desantis-accepted-luxury-hotel-stay-attend-right-wing-event/723598002/|title=DeSantis attended convention with speakers who have suggested killing Muslims, demeaned women|work=Naples Daily News|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis stated that his comment had \"zero to do with race\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/404355-desantis-monkey-comment-has-zero-to-do-with-race|title=DeSantis: 'Monkey' comment has 'zero to do with race'|work=TheHill.com|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=August 30, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Results ====\nInitial election-night results had DeSantis winning by nearly 100,000 votes, and Gillum conceded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/11/06/florida-governor-election-results-andrew-gillum-versus-ron-desantis/|title=Florida governor election results: Andrew Gillum versus Ron DeSantis|last=Wilson|first=Kirby|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> Gillum took back his concession as late-counted ballots brought the race within less than 34,000 votes, a margin of 0.4%. The close margin required an automatic machine recount of the ballots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/10/gillum-reverses-course-on-conceding-florida-governor-race.html|title=Gillum reverses course on conceding Florida governor race|date=2018-11-10|website=Cnbc.com|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\nA machine recount in three statewide contests (governor, [[2018 United States Senate election in Florida|U.S. senator]], and [[Florida Commissioner of Agriculture|agriculture commissioner]]) began with a deadline of November 15, 2018. Although three counties missed the deadline, it was not extended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/15/florida-recount-ron-desantis-prevails-over-andrew-gillum-governor/2006942002/|title=With Florida recount over, Andrew Gillum's last chance to become governor rests with the courts|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/416945-florida-senate-race-heads-to-a-hand-recount|title=Florida Senate race heads to a hand recount|last=Nam|first=Rafael|date=2018-11-15|website=TheHill.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> DeSantis was confirmed as the winner and Gillum conceded on November 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/17/politics/gillum-concedes-florida-governors-race-desantis/index.html|title=Andrew Gillum concedes Florida governor's race to Ron DeSantis|author1=Dan Merica|author2=Sophie Tatum|website=Cnn.com|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDeSantis prefiled the oath of office with the Florida Secretary of State and became governor at midnight, January 8, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/01/05/desantis-already-governor-when-ceremony-begins/|title=DeSantis already governor when ceremony begins|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]}}</ref> The official swearing in ceremony was held at noon that day. On January 11, 2019, DeSantis posthumously pardoned the [[Groveland Four]], four black men falsely convicted of rape in 1949.<ref name=\"ReasonGroveland\">{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Zuri |title=70 Years After They Were Wrongly Imprisoned, the Groveland Four Have Been Pardoned |url=https://reason.com/blog/2019/01/11/groveland-four-pardoned-after-70-years |website=Reason.com |accessdate=11 January 2019 |date=11 January 2019}}</ref> That same day, DeSantis officially suspended [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] [[sheriff]] [[Scott Israel]] for his response to the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]].\n\nIn his first two weeks in office, DeSantis appointed [[Barbara Lagoa]], [[Robert J. Luck]] and [[Carlos G. Mu\u00f1iz]] to fill the three vacancies on the [[Florida Supreme Court]], shifting the court from having a liberal to a conservative majority. He replaced the entire South Florida Water Management District board. He signed $2.5 billion executive order for water quality and Everglades restoration work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/political-roundtable-gov-desantis-actions-so-far-tampa-mayoral-race-gets-crowded-more|title=Political Roundtable: Gov. DeSantis&#039; Actions So Far, Tampa Mayoral Race Gets Crowded &amp; More|website=Wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu}}</ref> He created a [[Chief Science Officer|chief science officer]] position and created an office of coastal protection and resilience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/weekly-roundup-flexing-some-executive-muscle|title=Weekly Roundup: Flexing Some Executive Muscle|first=Dara Kam News Service of|last=Florida|date=January 11, 2019|website=Sunshinesstatenews.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, DeSantis signed an executive order calling for the end of [[Common Core]] in Florida.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Patrick | first1=Craig | title=Florida Gov. DeSantis signs executive order scrapping Common Core | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/florida-gov-desantis-signs-executive-order-scrapping-common-core | date=January 31, 2019 | publisher=[[Fox News]] (from [[WTVT]]) | accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis encouraged Florida sheriffs to cooperate with the federal government on immigration-related issues.<ref>{{cite web | title=Sheriffs look at options amid DeSantis immigration push | url=https://www.winknews.com/2019/03/12/sheriffs-look-at-options-amid-desantis-immigration-push/ | date=March 12, 2019 | publisher=[[WINK-TV]] | accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, DeSantis signed an anti-[[sanctuary city]] bill that requires law enforcement \"to honor U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement detainers for undocumented immigrants who are arrested or convicted\" of crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/advocates-say-florida-governor-sanctuary-bill-politically-motivated-n1017976|title=Advocates say Florida governor's 'sanctuary bill' politically motivated|website=NBC News|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ron-desantis-florida-sanctuary-immigration_n_5d03e0aae4b0985c419d439f|title=Florida Governor Signs Bill Banning Sanctuary Policies|date=June 14, 2019|website=HuffPost|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/florida-de-santis-signs-controversial-sanctuary-cities|title=Florida's DeSantis signs controversial sanctuary cities ban into law|first=Sam|last=Dorman|date=June 14, 2019|website=Fox News|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article231552873.html</ref> Florida became the 12th state to ban sanctuary cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/florida-becomes-th-state-to-ban-sanctuary-cities/article_a7382e03-4b84-5a79-a04b-f583959f7b5a.html|title=Florida becomes 12th state to ban sanctuary cities|first=Catherine E.|last=Shoichet|website=FOX Carolina|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, DeSantis signed a measure that would make it harder to launch successful ballot initiatives. Petition-gathering for ballot initiatives to legalize medical marijuana, increases to the minimum wage, and expansion of Medicaid were also under way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2019/06/07/ron-desantis-signs-crack-down-on-constitutional-amendments-solidifying-republican-control-in-florida/|title=Ron DeSantis signs crack down on constitutional amendments, solidifying Republican control in Florida|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://miami.cbslocal.com/2019/06/06/ballot-initiatives-measure-goes-to-florida-governor-ron-desantis/|title=Ballot Initiatives Measure Goes To Florida Governor Ron Desantis|date=2019-06-06|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/06/09/gov-desantis-signs-hb5-eviscerating-the-democratic-process-in-florida|title=Gov. DeSantis signs HB5, 'eviscerating' the democratic process in Florida|last=Florida|first=Jim Saunders, News Service of|website=Orlando Weekly|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, following on the heels of a 2018 constitutional amendment referendum in favor of voting rights restoration for felons, DeSantis signed legislation that restricted such restoration only to those felons who had fully paid back all fees and fines to the courts, a move that was criticized despite being in line with what the authors of the 2018 amendment has wanted in ''[[The New York Times]]'' as reminiscent of [[Poll taxes in the United States|poll taxes]] in the [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow]] South and prompted a lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/us/florida-felons-voting-rights.html|title=Florida Limits Ex-Felon Voting, Prompting a Lawsuit and Cries of \u2018Poll Tax\u2019|last=Mazzei|first=Patricia|date=2019-06-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn August&nbsp;28, 2019, DeSantis declared a state of emergency for 26 counties in [[Hurricane Dorian]]'s expected path.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/08/28/governor-ron-desantis-declares-state-of-emergency-urges-floridians-to-prepare-for-hurricane-dorian/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis Declares State of Emergency, Urges Floridians to Prepare for Hurricane Dorian|publisher=Government of Florida|date=August 28, 2019|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> This later expanded to the entire state on August&nbsp;29.\n\nIn March 2020 DeSantis decided against declaring a state of emergency in [[Florida]] during the [[Corona pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-update-governor-ron-desantis-calls-for-major-disaster-declaration-for-florida/ar-BB11E0A4|title=Coronavirus Update: Governor Ron DeSantis Calls For Major Disaster Declaration For Florida|publisher=MSN News|date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/25/gov-ron-desantis-wont-shut-down-florida-heres-who-hes-talking-to-about-that|title=Gov. Ron DeSantis won\u2019t shut down Florida. Here\u2019s who he\u2019s talking to about that.\n|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|date=March, 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Representative Ron DeSantis, Iran's Missile Program (17983165814).jpg|thumbnail|right|DeSantis speaking at the Hudson Institute in June 2015]]\nDeSantis is a conservative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2017/12/22/trump-endorses-desantis-for-governor-via-twitter-161236|title=Trump endorses DeSantis for governor via Twitter|work=Politico PRO|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/05/07/404805852/meet-the-tea-partys-new-favorite-candidate|title=Meet The Tea Party's New Favorite Candidate|publisher=NPR|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/ron-desantis-tea-party-favorite-becomes-first-republican-to-enter-senate-race-7597712|title=Ron DeSantis, Tea Party Favorite, Becomes First Republican to Enter Senate Race|last=Munzenrieder|first=Kyle|date=May 6, 2015|work=Miami New Times|access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> He was endorsed by the [[Family Research Council Action PAC]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac |title=Ron DeSantis endorsed by Common Core opponent FRC Action PAC|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|date=November 23, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Orlando Political Observer|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125162156/http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac|archivedate=November 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Marijuana ===\nDeSantis supports the implementation of a medical marijuana program in Florida, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"floridapolitics.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gainesville.com/news/20180601/legalizing-cannabis-divides-candidates-for-governor|title=Legalizing cannabis divides candidates for governor|first=George Bennett Palm Beach|last=Post|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> He voted against the Veterans Equal Access Amendment that would give veterans access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.safeaccessnow.org/veteran_2017_blumenauer|title=2016 Congressional Scorecard|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Contraceptives and abortion ===\nDeSantis [[Opposition to abortion|opposes abortion]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424801/planned-parenthood-chief-abortion-survivor-baby-entitled-medical-care-joel-gehrke|title=Planned Parenthood Head: An Abortion Survivor is a 'Baby' Entitled to Medical Care|last1=Gehkre|first1=Joel|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=National Review}}</ref> and has denounced [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/186587-ron-desantis-denounces-planned-parenthoods-loathsome-practice|title=Ron DeSantis denounces Planned Parenthood's alleged \"loathsome practice\" |last1=Gancarski|first1=A.G.|date=July 15, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis agreed with the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.]]'', saying \"This case does not concern the availability or legality of contraceptives, and individuals can obtain and use these as they see fit. The question is simply whether the government can force the owners of Hobby Lobby to pay for abortifacients in violation of their faith.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/florida-congressmen-divide-over-hobby-lobby-case|title=Florida Congressmen Divide Over Hobby Lobby Case|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy ===\nDeSantis has said that the debate in Washington, D.C., over how to reduce the deficit should shift emphasis from tax increases to curtailing spending and triggering economic growth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Douglas|title=DeSantis emphasizes importance of economic growth|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2012-12-15/desantis-economic-growth-essential |accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=December 16, 2012}}</ref> He supports a \"no budget no pay\" policy for Congress to encourage the passage of a budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wexler|first1=Gene|title=New St. Johns Rep. opens up on financial and governmental reforms|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/news/local/new-st-johns-rep-opens-financial-and-governmental-/nTmcb |accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=WOKV|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> He believes the [[Federal Reserve System]] should be audited.<ref name=roll/>\n\nIn the wake of the alleged [[IRS targeting controversy]], DeSantis called for the resignation of Internal Revenue Service commissioner [[John Koskinen]] for having \"failed the American people by frustrating Congress's attempts to ascertain the truth.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Jordan|first2=Jim|title=The Stonewall at the Top of the IRS|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-stonewall-at-the-top-of-the-irs-1438039060|accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Mitch|title=Ron DeSantis wants Obama to remove IRS commissioner\u2014or else |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187207-ron-desantis-wants-obama-to-remove-irs-commissioner-or-else|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 28, 2015}}</ref> He co-sponsored a bill to impeach Koskinen for violating the public's trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oversight.house.gov/release/resolution-introduced-impeach-irs-commissioner|title=Resolution Introduced to Impeach IRS Commissioner|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=House Oversight Committee|date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, DeSantis was named \"Taxpayer Superhero\" by [[Citizens Against Government Waste]], a conservative think-tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gancarski|first1=July 31, 2015|title=Email insights: Ron DeSantis, \"Taxpayer Superhero\" |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187434-email-insights-ron-desantis-taxpayer-superhero|accessdate=February 28, 2016 |publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supported the [[Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act|Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny (REINS) Act]], which would require that regulations that have a significant economic impact be subject to a vote of Congress prior to taking effect.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siefring|first1=Neil|title=The REINS Act will keep regulations and their costs in check |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/economy-budget/250178-the-reins-act-will-keep-regulations-and-their-costs-in |accessdate=February 28, 2016|newspaper=The Hill|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis introduced the [[Let Seniors Work Act]], which would repeal the [[Earnings test (US)|Retirement Earnings Test]] and exempt senior citizens from the 12.4% [[Federal Insurance Contributions Act tax|Social Security payroll tax]], and he co-sponsored a measure to eliminate taxes on [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin |title=Marco Rubio, Ron DeSantis Restore 'Let Seniors Work Act'|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/marco-rubio-ron-desantis-restore-let-seniors-work-act|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis sponsored the Transportation Empowerment Act, which would transfer much of the responsibility for transportation projects to the individual states and sharply reduce the [[federal gas tax]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laing|first1=Keith|title=Bill filed to sharply reduce the gas tax|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/244597-bill-filed-to-eliminate-the-gas-tax|accessdate=February 28, 2016|newspaper=The Hill|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Mike|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Economy Commentary Let America Fix the Highways Washington Broke|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/10/let-america-fix-the-highways-washington-broke|accessdate=February 28, 2016|work=The Daily Signal|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis has opposed legislation to require online retailers to collect and pay state sales tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dixon |first1=Matt|title=Retail group assails DeSantis over Internet sales tax|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2013-06-27#.VtONM_HvOac|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122017\">{{cite news|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah |title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> DeSantis says the bill will bring a \"dramatically lower tax rate\" and \"full expensing of capital investments.\" DeSantis also believes the act will bring more jobs to America.<ref name=\"Brown121917\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Stephanie|title=Northeast Florida lawmakers divided on impact of tax reform plan |website=Wokv.com|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/local/northeast-florida-lawmakers-divided-impact-gop-tax-reform-plan/vyBF5BQ8kPldHOvKT0JGdK/|publisher=WOKV Radio|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nDeSantis opposes federal education programs such as [[No Child Left Behind Act]] and [[Race to the Top]], saying that education policy should be made at the local level.<ref name=roll>{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis, R-Fla. (6th District) |url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/ron-desantis-house-r-fla-6.html|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis introduced the [[Higher Education Reform and Opportunity Act]], which would allow states to create their own accreditation systems. In an op-ed for the ''[[National Review]]'', DeSantis said that his legislation would give students \"access to federal loan money to put towards non-traditional educational opportunities, such as online learning courses, vocational schools, and apprenticeships in skilled trades.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Lee|first2=Mike|title=Break Up the Higher-Ed Cartel|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/414848/break-higher-ed-cartel-ron-desantis-mike-lee|accessdate=February 29, 2016 |work=National Review|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign relations===\n[[File:President Trump Delivers Remarks to the Venezuelan-American Community (47096114742).jpg|thumb|DeSantis watches as President [[Donald Trump]] delivers remarks to the [[Venezuelan Americans|Venezuelan American]] community in February 2019]]\n\n====Cuba====\nIn 2015, DeSantis introduced the Guantanamo Bay Recidivism Prevention Act, which would cut off foreign aid to countries that receive detainees if they show back up on the terrorism recidivism list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis: Releasing Guantanamo Detainees is a Security Threat|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/ron-desanits-releasing-guantanamo-detainees-security-threat|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis opposed [[Barack Obama|President Obama]]'s plan to shut down the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]], saying \"Bringing hardened terrorists to the U.S. homeland harms our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Obama's GITMO Proposal Draws Fire From GOP Candidates Vying to Replace Marco Rubio|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/obamas-gitmo-propsoal-draws-fire-gop-candidates-vying-replace-marco-rubio|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the formal restart of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and Cuba, DeSantis said \"Raising the Cuban flag in the United States is a slap in the face to those who have experienced the brutality of the Castro regime.\"<ref name=reaction>{{cite news |last1=Leary|first1=Alex|title=Florida reaction to Cuba news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/florida-reaction-to-cuba-news/2237995|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nDeSantis opposed the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]], calling it \"a bad deal that will significantly degrade our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotton|first1=Tom|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Congress Must Reject the Iran Deal |url=http://time.com/3978510/congress-must-reject-the-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Time|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis said \"the Iran deal gives Ayatollah Khamenei exactly what he wants: billions of dollars in sanctions relief, validation of the Iranian nuclear program, and the ability to stymie inspections.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeSantis Condemns Deal as a Gift to Iran's Ayatollah|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/desantis-condemns-deal-as-a-gift-to-irans-ayatollah |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a line of questioning, DeSantis told Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] that the executive branch had a legal obligation to provide Congress with the details behind any side deals made between world leaders and Iran.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank |title=DeSantis and Kerry get contentious over Iran Deal|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/07/29/desantis-and-kerry-get-contentious-over-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Orlando Political Observer|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis accused President Barack Obama of giving better treatment of Cuba's [[Raul Castro]] and Iran's Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] than of Israel's [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=save>{{cite news|last1=Man|first1=Anthony|title='We need to save the country', conservative U.S. Senate candidate tells Broward activists|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ron-desantis-conservative-candidate-20150824-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nIn 2013, DeSantis introduced the Palestinian Accountability Act, which would halt U.S. aid to the [[Palestinian National Authority|Palestinian Authority]] until it formally recognizes [[Israel]]'s right to exist as a Jewish state and cuts off all ties with the militant group [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kredo|first1=Adam|title=House Bill Would Cut Aid to Palestinian Authority |url=http://freebeacon.com/national-security/house-bill-would-cut-aid-to-palestinian-authority|accessdate=February 26, 2016 |work=Washington Free Beacon|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis co-introduced the Non-Discrimination of Israel in Labeling Act, which will defend the right of Israeli producers to label products manufactured in the West Bank as \"Israel,\" \"Made in Israel,\" or \"Product of Israel.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganckarski |first1=A.G.|title=Ron DeSantis co-introduces non-discrimination of Israel in labeling act |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/201890-ron-desantis-co-introduces-non-discrimination-of-israel-in-labeling-act |accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis supported the move of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/05/13/scott-desantis-in-israel-for-u-s-embassy-opening/ |title=Scott, DeSantis in Israel for U.S. Embassy opening |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=May 13, 2018 |accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs governor, in light of [[Airbnb]]'s decision to no longer allow rentals of [[Israeli settlement]]s in the [[West Bank]], on January 15, 2019, DeSantis directed the Department of Management Services to no longer reimburse state employees and state contractors for travel expenses incurred with Airbnb;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/01/15/governor-ron-desantis-announces-actions-to-affirm-floridas-support-of-israel/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis Announces Actions to Affirm Florida's Support of Israel|website=Flgov.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> later that month he accepted the recommendation of the State Board of Administration to place Airbnb on Florida's \"Scrutinized Companies List\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flgov.com/2019/01/29/governor-ron-desantis-statement-on-cabinet-decision-placing-airbnb-on-scrutinized-companies-list/|title=Governor Ron DeSantis' Statement on Cabinet Decision Placing Airbnb on Scrutinized Companies List|website=Flgov.com|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Government===\nDeSantis opted not to receive his [[congressional pension]], and he filed a measure that would eliminate pensions for members of Congress.<ref name=roll/> After introducing the End Pensions in Congress Act, DeSantis said \"The Founding Fathers envisioned elected officials as part of a servant class, yet Washington has evolved into a ruling class culture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harper |first1=Jennifer|title=No more 'ruling class culture': New legislation would jettison pensions for Congress |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/2/no-more-ruling-class-culture-new-legislaiton-would/|accessdate=February 28, 2016 |work=The Washington Times|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supports a constitutional amendment to impose [[term limit]]s for members of Congress, so that representatives would be limited to three terms and senators to two terms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brendan|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html |accessdate=February 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gun law===\nDeSantis opposes [[gun control]]. He received an A+ rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keller |first1=Michael|title=This is Your Representative on Guns |url=http://thedailybeast.thisisyourreponguns.com/#Pane=overview&Chamber=House|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Daily Beast |date=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\nHe is generally opposed to firearm regulation, saying, \"Very rarely do firearms restrictions affect criminals. They really only affect law-abiding citizens.\"<ref name=\"Maddock 2013\">{{cite news| title=Ron DeSantis Put On Spot By Sandy Hook Parents At Florida Town Hall |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/20/ron-desantis-sandy-hook_n_2726089.html|last=Maddock|first=Preston |date=February 20, 2013 |work=HuffPost |accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2018 [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in [[Parkland, Florida]], DeSantis expressed his support for hiring retired [[law enforcement officer]]s and military [[veteran]]s as armed guards for schools.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\">{{cite news |last=Bennett |first=George |date=February 20, 2018 |title=Ron DeSantis: Enlist retired military, cops to prevent school shootings |url=http://postonpolitics.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2018/02/20/ron-desantis-enlist-retired-military-cops-to-prevent-school-shootings/ |work=The Palm Beach Post |location=Palm Beach, Florida |access-date=February 23, 2018 }}</ref> He disagrees with legislation signed into law by Florida governor Rick Scott that banned bump stocks, added a mandatory three-day waiting period for gun purchases, and raised the legal age for purchases from 18 to 21.<ref name=Mahoney-082918/> He has expressed support for measures to improve federal background checks for purchasing firearms and has said that there is a need to intervene with those who are exhibiting warning signs of committing violence instead of waiting until a crime has been committed.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\"/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nDeSantis is opposed to the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"Repeal\">{{cite press release|title=Rep. DeSantis Statement on ObamaCare Repeal|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-desantis-statement-on-obamacare-repeal |publisher=Office of Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Moorhead|first1=Molly |title=Florida Rep. Ron DeSantis says 'Obamacare' tax is cheaper than insurance|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/jan/24/ron-desantis/desantis-says-obamacare-tax-cheaper-insurance/|accessdate=February 27, 2016 |publisher=PolitiFact|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He has called for the \"full and complete repeal\" of the act.<ref name=\"Repeal\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, DeSantis said that he wasn't ready to support the [[American Health Care Act]], the House Republican effort to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tony Perry|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gops-darrell-issa-represents-a-clear-test-for-anti-trump-democrats-trying-for-electoral-gains-in-2018/2017/03/11/5d20b0f0-05ed-11e7-ad5b-d22680e18d10_story.html|title=GOP's Darrell Issa represents a clear test for anti-Trump Democrats trying for electoral gains in 2018 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> He did vote for the May 2017 Republican effort to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2018/09/10/democrats-launch-website-attacking-desantiscare-600996|title=Democrats launch website attacking 'DeSantisCare'|work=Politico PRO|access-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html |title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill|last=Aisch|first=Gregor|access-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of March 2020, Florida had 6,741 confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|covid-19]], however DeSantis would not issue a statewide \u201cstay-at-home\u201d order because the Trump administration had not recommended that he do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/04/01/coronavirus-florida-desantis/|title=Florida covid-19 cases surge to nearly 7,000 as Ron DeSantis resists statewide restrictions|date=April 1, 2020|author=Barbash, Fred|accessdate=April 1, 2020|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> Then on April 1, DeSantis ordered that all Floridians stay home for 30 days with exceptions for essential services and activities.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rohrer, Gray and Lemongello, Steven|date=April 1, 2020|title=DeSantis announces statewide shutdown order for Florida through April|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/os-ne-coronavirus-desantis-wednesday-20200401-yc2ttrxuw5hx7ci3zn2id3ynlq-story.html|accessdate=April 1, 2020|publisher=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nDeSantis was a critic of President Obama's immigration policies; he opposed Obama's deferred action programs ([[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA) and [[Deferred Action for Parents of Americans]] (DAPA) and accused him of failing to enforce immigration laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/ron-desantis-turns-heat-obama-failing-enforce-immigration-laws |title=Ron DeSantis Turns Up the Heat on Obama for Failing to Enforce Immigration Laws|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/17/before-skeptical-lawmakers-officials-defend-legality-of-obamas-immigration-actions|title=Before Skeptical Lawmakers, Officials Defend 'Legality' of Obama's Immigration Actions|last1=Scanlon|first1=Kate|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Daily Signal}}</ref> DeSantis opposes \"sanctuary cities.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/4358373421001/sanctuary-cities-under-fire-/?#sp=show-clips|title=\u2190 Shrink player Sanctuary cities under fire|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016 |publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref> He is a co-sponsor of the Establishing Mandatory Minimums for Illegal Reentry Act of 2015, also known as Kate's Law, which would amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to increase penalties applicable to aliens who unlawfully reenter the United States after being removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trackbill.com/bill/us-hr3011-kates-law/1198394|title=HR3011 Kate's Law|publisher=TrackBill|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, DeSantis spoke at [[ACT! for America]], an anti-Muslim advocacy group.<ref name=-180917>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/09/17/ron-desantis-act-america-address/1333447002/ |title=Florida's Ron DeSantis spoke to group whose founder says devout Muslims can't be loyal Americans |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 17, 2018 |first=Trevor |last=Aaronson}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], DeSantis \"called for urgent recognition that Islamic extremism is to blame for the Paris attacks and should be seen as an enemy for America.\" DeSantis has said \"The enemy is an ideology rooted in militant Islam\" and has said that [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] must be stopped and its members kept away from America.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-sunshine-summit-senate-candidates-20151114-story.html|title=GOP Senate candidates call for fight against Islamic militants after Paris attacks|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref> Regarding U.S. policy toward refugees, DeSantis said \"the prudent policy is to err on the side of protecting the American people\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2015/11/27/rep-ron-desantis-on-refugee-debate-err-on-side-protecting-american-people/|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis on refugee debate: 'Err on side of protecting the American people' |date=November 27, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Fox News Channel}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT issues===\nDeSantis has a \"0\" rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] based on his record of voting on [[LGBT rights|LGBT]]-related issues and legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2016/10/07/rubios-score-plummets-to-0-in-hrc-congressional-ratings |title=Rubio's score plummets to '0' in HRC congressional ratings|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|date=October 7, 2016|newspaper=[[Washington Blade]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, he told the ''Sun Sentinel'' he \"doesn't want any discrimination in Florida, I want people to be able to live their life, whether you're gay or whether you're religious.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/104830236-132.html|title=Ron DeSantis answered question on his stance on gay rights|website=Sun-Sentinel|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, less than a week after taking office, DeSantis issued a nondiscrimination order for state employees reiterating former governor [[Rick Scott|Scott]]'s order; while the order included [[race (human categorization)|race]], [[ageing|age]], [[sex]], [[ethnic group|color]], [[religion]], [[nationality|national origin]], [[marriage|marital status]] and [[disability]], it included no protections for [[sexual orientation]] or [[gender identity]]. [[Equality Florida]] strongly criticized DeSantis, with the organization's senior political director stating that Equality Florida was \"deeply disappointed to see that LGBTQ employees and contractors have been left out of the governor's executive order.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2019/01/09/new-fla-guv-excludes-lgbt-people-from-non-discrimination-order/|title=New Fla. guv excludes LGBT people from non-discrimination order|newspaper=Washington Blade|author=Chris Johnson|date=9 January 2019}}</ref> DeSantis's predecessor had pledged to sign an LGBT-inclusive order as governor, but ultimately did not follow through on the grounds that proper federal protections existed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/01/10/florida-gov-ron-desantis-excludes-lgbtq-protections-from-anti-discrimination-order|title=Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis excludes LGBTQ protections from anti-discrimination order|newspaper=Orlando Weekly|author=Monivette Cordeiro|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, DeSantis' office issued a proclamation honoring the victims of the June 12, 2016 [[Orlando nightclub shooting]] at the [[Pulse nightclub|Pulse]] [[gay bar]] and [[nightclub]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], where 49 people were killed and 50 others were injured by [[Omar Mateen]]. The proclamation did not include any reference to the LGBT community, sparking severe criticism and accusations that the governor intentionally omitted the category from the message; [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Florida House of Representatives|state representatives]] [[Anna Eskamani]] and [[Carlos Guillermo Smith]], who is openly gay, lambasted the governor, while [[gun control]] activist [[Fred Guttenberg]], whose daughter was killed in a [[school shooting]] [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|in Broward County a year earlier]], questioned if the omission was predetermined. DeSantis reissued the proclamation with revisions including mentions of the LGBT community, and a spokesperson stated that the omission was due to an error on the part of DeSantis' staff. Former Governor Scott included an LGBT reference in a prior Pulse memorial message.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2019/06/12/desantis-does-about-face-after-omitting-lgbtq-from-pulse-proclamation-1058537|title=DeSantis does about-face after omitting LGBTQ from Pulse proclamation|publisher=Politico|author=Matt Dixon, Gary Fineout|date=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Russia investigation===\nAccording to the ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'', DeSantis \"made a name for himself&nbsp;[in&nbsp;2017] attacking special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation&nbsp;into Russian meddling in the 2016 election.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/05/rep-ron-desantis-declares-run-for-florida-governor|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis declares run for Florida governor|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis proposed an amendment that would halt funding for Mueller's [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|2017 Special Counsel investigation]] probe six months after the amendment's passage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amendments-rules.house.gov/amendments/DESANT_055_xml824171651535153.pdf|title=Amendment to Division C of the Rules Committee Print 115-31 Offered by Mr. DeSantis of Florida|website=Amendments-rules.house.gov|format=PDF|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> In addition, this provision would prohibit Mueller from investigating matters that occurred before June 2015, when Trump launched his presidential campaign.<ref>Austin Wright, [http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108 Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months], Politico.com, August 28, 2017.</ref> In December 2017, DeSantis asserted that if there was any evidence of collusion between members of the Trump campaign and Russian officials, it would already have been leaked.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/366923-judiciary-republican-if-there-was-any-trump-russia-collusion-it-would-have|title=Judiciary Republican: If there was any Trump-Russia collusion, it would have leaked months ago|last=Manchester|first=Julia |date=December 31, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, while on the House Intelligence Committee, DeSantis voted on party lines to release a classified memo authored by Republicans on the committee which purported to show that the FBI abused its surveillance powers in the Russia investigation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/house-vote-releasing-classified-nunes-memo-about-fbi-eavesdropping-n842311|title=House intelligence panel votes to release classified Nunes memo about FBI eavesdropping|publisher=NBC News |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis voted not to release a memo authored by Democrats on the committee which accused the Republicans on the committee of playing politics with national security.<ref name=\":0\"/> Democrats described the Republican-authored memo as grossly distorted and intended to discredit the Mueller Special Counsel investigation, and said that the Republicans on the committee had begun an investigation into the FBI and DOJ.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, DeSantis called on FBI director [[Christopher A. Wray|Christopher Wray]] to criminally investigate a number of officials involved in investigating Russian interference in the 2016 election, including former FBI director [[James Comey]], former acting director of the FBI [[Andrew McCabe]], FBI agent [[Peter Strzok]] and FBI counsel [[Lisa Page]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/384312-trump-to-lawmakers-pressing-sessions-on-comey-good-luck-with-that|title=Trump to lawmakers pressing Sessions to investigate Comey and Clinton: 'Good luck with that'|last=Shelbourne|first=Mallory|date=April 22, 2018 |work=TheHill|access-date=April 24, 2018}}</ref> DeSantis also called for investigations of a number of former Obama officials, including [[Loretta Lynch]] and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/18/trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations-532516|title=trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2019, a spokesman for DeSantis announced that he would be \"returning a political contribution he received from two Soviet-born businessmen, [[Lev Parnas and Igor Fruman]], through their company Global Energy Producers. Parnas and Fruman are accused of funneling foreign cash into U.S. elections to increase their influence and promote their business interests; they are central figures in the Trump-Ukraine scandal and impeachment inquiry. \"They made the donation a day before Trump tweeted his 'full endorsement' of DeSantis.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-ne-campaign-finance-indictments-20191010-jwao3r2q3vd4ff3jpsprrl5azu-story.html|title=Gov. Ron DeSantis to return campaign cash from indicted South Florida businessmen with Giuliani ties|last=Swisher, Skyler|first=Chokey, Aric & Gray, Rohrer|date=October 10, 2019|work=South Florida Sun Sentinel|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans===\nDeSantis has sharply criticized the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] for the [[Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014]], in which veteran deaths were linked to wait times. He co-sponsored the VA Accountability Act, which aims to increase accountability by providing for the removal or demotion of employees of the Department of Veterans Affairs based on performance or misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winslow|first1=Hailey|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis pushes legislation to hold Veterans Affairs accountable|url=http://www.news4jax.com/news/florida/st-johns-county/congressman-ron-desantis-pushes-legislation-to-hold-veterans-affairs-accountable|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=News 4 Jax|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis |first1=Clifford|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis pushes for VA reform in St. Augustine|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/politics/2014-05-05/story/rep-ron-desantis-pushes-va-reform-st-augustine|accessdate=February 27, 2016|newspaper=[[Florida Times Union]]|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the Post-9/11 Veterans Caucus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Porter|first1=Thomas|title=IAVA Team Continues to Seek Path Forward for 9/11 First Responders|url=http://iava.org/blogs/iava-team-continues-to-seek-path-forward-for-911-first-responders-press-conference-tomorrow|publisher=Iraq & Afghanistan Veterans of America|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting rights ===\n{{As of|August 2018}}, DeSantis had not taken a position on a November 2018 ballot initiative on the restoration of voting rights for felons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/30/where-they-stand-candidates-for-governor-on-vote-for-felons/|title=Where they stand: Candidates for governor on vote for felons|last=Bousquet|first=Steve|date=January 30, 2018|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Pantazi-180824>{{cite web |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180817/floridas-prisons-are-more-expensive-than-ever-what-will-next-governor-do-about-it |title=Florida's prisons are more expensive than ever. What will the next governor do about it?|work=[[Florida Times-Union]]|date=August 24, 2018|accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Andrew|last=Pantazi}}</ref>\n\n===Law enforcement===\nDeSantis called for [[Broward County Sheriff's Office|Broward County Sheriff]] [[Scott Israel]] to resign after the Parkland school shooting committed by [[Nikolas Cruz]]. Israel was accused by a large number of people of running his department poorly and not properly handling or responding to the shooting. DeSantis stated that had he been governor when the shooting occurred he would have removed Israel from his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20181212/exclusive-desantis-to-act-quickly-on-water-supreme-court-broward-sheriff|title=EXCLUSIVE: DeSantis to act quickly on water, Supreme Court, Broward sheriff|first=George|last=Bennett|date=December 12, 2018|newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ss1112019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-ne-sheriff-israel-suspension-20190111-story.html |title=Sheriff Scott Israel: Career defined by controversy and fury over failures during Parkland shooting |last=Swisher |first=Skyler |date=January 11, 2019 |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> On January 11, shortly after taking office as governor, DeSantis suspended Israel from his duties. Israel declared that he intends to contest his suspension.<ref name=\"ss1112019\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Ron DeSantis and Casey DeSantis.jpg|thumb|Ron and Casey DeSantis in January 2019]]\nDeSantis is a [[Roman Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.cq.com/members/46138|title=RollCall.com \u2013 Member Profile \u2013 Rep. Ron DeSantis, R-Fla.|website=Media.cq.com}}</ref> and of Italian descent. In 2010, he married [[Casey DeSantis|Casey Black]]. They lived in [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida|Ponte Vedra Beach]], near [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]] until Ponte Vedra Beach was drawn into the neighboring [[Florida's 4th congressional district|4th district]]. DeSantis and his wife then moved to [[Palm Coast, Florida|Palm Coast]], north of Daytona Beach.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Harper |url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/news/20160729/congressman-ron-desantis-moves-to-flagler-county|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis moves to Flagler County|website=News-journalonline.com|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|title=Ronald Dion DeSantis \u2013 Florida Resident Database|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019033354/https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|archivedate=October 19, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis and his wife have two daughters and a son. <ref>{{cite tweet | last = DeSantis | first = Casey | user = FLCaseyDeSantis | number = 1244601703795765248 | date = 30 March 2020 | title = Ron and I are beyond blessed to welcome our new baby girl, Mamie to the world. At 7 lbs 4 oz she was the smallest of the bunch, but she is already holding her own. Madison and Mason are so excited for their new baby sister! | access-date = 30 March 2020 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.flgov.com/ official Florida Governor website]\n* [https://rondesantis.com// Campaign website]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Ron_DeSantis_%5BR-06%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rondesantis}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=D000621 |votesmart=137630 |fec=H2FL00292 |congress=ron-desantis/D000621 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cliff Stearns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Florida's 6th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Waltz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Florida]]|years=[[2018 Florida gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Scott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Florida]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Florida}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br/>in which event is held}}\n